# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amelioration-act-1798
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The **1811 German Coast uprising** was a slave rebellion which occurred in the Territory of Orleans on January 8–10, 1811.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] It occurred on the east bank of the Mississippi River in the modern-day Louisiana parishes of St.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebellion was the largest of its kind in the history of the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels killed two white slave owner family members, but the confrontations with the U.S. military and local militiamen who were sent to suppress the rebellion, combined with post-trial executions, resulted in the deaths of 95 rebels.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 8, between 64 and 125 slaves ignited a fight for freedom and marched from plantations in and near present-day LaPlace, Louisiana on the German Coast towards New Orleans.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] More people escaped slavery and joined them along the way, and some accounts claimed a total of 200 to 500 people escaped and participated in the rebellion.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] During their two-day, 20 mi (32 km)-long march the rebels, armed mostly with improvised weapons, burned five plantations along with several sugarhouses and crop fields.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] After a few planters were killed and others attacked, White settlers led by U.S. officials formed militia companies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] In battle on January 10 they killed 40 to 45 of the people escaping slavery, while suffering no fatalities themselves, then hunted down and killed several other people without trial.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Over the next two weeks, White planters and U.S. officials interrogated, tried, executed, and decapitated an additional 44 people escaping slavery who had been captured.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Executions were generally by hanging or firing squad.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Heads were displayed on pikes to intimidate others.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration in January of the uprising, in which they have been joined by some descendants of participants in the revolt.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sugar boom on what was known as Louisiana's German Coast (named for immigrants in the 1720s) began after the American Revolutionary War, while the area near New Orleans was still controlled by Spain.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the 1780s Jean Saint Malo, an escaped slave, established a colony of maroons in the swamps below New Orleans, which eventually led Spanish officials to send militia to capture him.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Saint Malo became a folk hero after his execution in New Orleans on June 19, 1784.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] A decade later, during the height of the French Revolution, Spanish officials discovered a slave conspiracy at Pointe Coupee (established by French settlers around 1720 between Natchez and New Orleans).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] That slave uprising during the Easter holidays was suppressed before it came to fruition and resulted in 23 executions by hanging (with the severed heads then displayed on the road to New Orleans), and 31 additional slaves were flogged and sent to serve hard labor in other Spanish outposts.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the Haitian Revolution, planters established similar lucrative sugarcane plantations in the Gulf Coast area, resulting in a dense slave population.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] They converted from cotton and indigo plantations to sugarcane, so that by 1802, 70 sugar plantations produced over 3,000 tons annually.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some accounts claimed blacks outnumbered whites by nearly five to one by 1810, and about 90% of whites in the area enslaved people.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] More than half of those enslaved may have been born outside Louisiana, many in Africa, where various European nations established slave trading outposts and Kongo was ripped apart by civil wars.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the U.S. negotiated the Louisiana Purchase in 1803, both the Marquis de Lafayette and James Monroe declined to become the governor of the Territory of Orleans.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] President Thomas Jefferson then turned to a fellow Virginian, William C.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne, whom he appointed on an interim basis and who arrived in New Orleans with 350 volunteers and 18 boats.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne struggled with the area's diverse population, particularly because he spoke neither French nor Spanish.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The population also included a larger proportion of native Africans among the slaves than elsewhere in the U.S.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] In addition, the mixed-race Creole and French-speaking population grew markedly with refugees from Haiti (and their slaves) following the successful Haitian Revolution.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne was not used to a society with the number of free people of color that Louisiana had, but he worked to continue their role in the militia that had been established under Spanish rule.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Long-term French Creole residents complained to Washington, D.C., about Claiborne and new U.S. settlers in the territory, and wanted no part of President Jefferson's plan to pay 30,000 Americans to move into the new territory and amalgamate with the residents.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, by 1805, a delegation led by Jean Noël Destréhan went to Washington to complain about the "oppressive and degrading" form of the territorial government, but President Madison continued to support Claiborne, who had expressed great doubts about the planters' honesty and trustworthiness.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Lastly, Claiborne suspected that the Spanish in nearby West Florida might encourage an insurrection.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, he struggled to establish and maintain his authority.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the overall Territory of Orleans, from 1803 to 1811, the free black population nearly tripled, to 5,000, with 3,000 arriving as migrants from Haiti (via Cuba) in 1809–1810.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] In Saint-Domingue they had enjoyed certain rights as *gens de couleur*, including owning slaves themselves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Furthermore, between 1790 and 1810, slave traders brought around 20,000 enslaved Africans to New Orleans.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The masters and slaves were virtually all Catholic.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The waterways and bayous around New Orleans and Lake Pontchartrain made transportation and trade possible but also provided easy escapes and nearly impenetrable hiding places for runaway slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some maroon colonies continued for years within several miles of New Orleans.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] With the spread of ideas of freedom from the French and Haitian Revolutions, European Americans worried about slave uprisings, particularly in the Louisiana area.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 1805, they heard a traveling Frenchman was preaching about liberty, equality, and fraternity to the French-speaking slaves, and arrested him as dangerous.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] A group of slaves met on January 6, 1811.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] It was a period when work had relaxed on the plantations after the fierce weeks of the sugar harvest and processing.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] As planter James Brown testified weeks later, "The black Quamana [Kwamena, meaning "born on Saturday"], owned by Mr.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Brown, and the mulatto Harry, owned by Messrs.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Kenner and Henderson, were at the home of Manuel Andry on the night of Saturday–Sunday of the current month in order to deliberate with the mulatto Charles Deslondes, chief of the brigands." Slaves had spread word of the planned uprising among the slaves at plantations up and down the German Coast.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The revolt began on January 8 at the Andry plantation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] After striking and badly wounding Andry, the slaves killed his son Gilbert.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] "An attempt was made to assassinate me by the stroke of an axe", Andry wrote.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] "My poor son has been ferociously murdered by a horde of brigands who from my plantation to that of Mr.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The approximately 15 slaves at Andry's plantation, about 30 miles (50 km) upriver from New Orleans, joined another eight slaves from the next-door plantation of the widows of Jacques and Georges Deslondes.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] This was the home plantation of Charles Deslondes, a slave driver (a slave overseer of other slaves) later described by one of the captured slaves as the "principal chief of the brigands".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Small groups of slaves joined from every plantation the rebels passed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Witnesses remarked on their organized march.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] They carried mostly pikes, hoes, and axes, but few firearms, and they marched to drums while some carried flags.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Approximately 10–25% of any given plantation's slave population joined with them.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the plantation of James Brown, Kook, one of the most active participants and key figures in the story of the uprising, joined the insurrection.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the next plantation down, Kook attacked and killed François Trépagnier with an axe.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] He was the second and last planter killed in the rebellion.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the band of slaves passed the LaBranche plantation, they stopped at the home of the local physician.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Finding him gone, Kook set his house on fire.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some planters testified at the trials in parish courts that they were warned by slaves of the uprising.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Others regularly stayed in New Orleans, where many had town houses, and trusted their plantations to overseers to run.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Planters quickly crossed the Mississippi River to escape the insurrection and to raise a militia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] As those escaping moved downriver, they passed larger plantations, from which other slaves joined them.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Numerous slaves joined the insurrection from the Meuillion plantation, the largest and wealthiest plantation on the German Coast.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels laid waste to Meuillion's house.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] They tried to set it on fire, but a slave named Bazile fought the fire and saved the house.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising started in present-day LaPlace and followed a 20-mile trek on the old River Road through the present-day towns of Montz, Norco, New Sarpy, Destrehan, St.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Rose and ended at much of what had once been the Kenner and Henderson Plantations and is now Rivertown and Louis Armstrong International Airport in Kenner.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] After nightfall the escaping slaves reached Cannes-Brulées, about 15 miles (24 km) northwest of New Orleans.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The men had traveled between 14 and 22 miles (23 and 35 km), a march that probably took them seven to ten hours.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] By some accounts, they numbered "some 200 slaves", although other accounts estimated up to 500.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] As typical of revolts of most classes, free or slave, the insurgent slaves were mostly young men between the ages of 20 and 30.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] They represented primarily lower-skilled occupations on the sugar plantations, where slaves labored in difficult conditions with a low life expectancy.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Despite his injuries, Andry crossed the river and made contact with other planters, raising a militia and pursuing the escaping slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] By noon on January 9, the residents of New Orleans had heard about the insurrection.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] By sunset, General Wade Hampton I, Commodore John Shaw, and Claiborne sent two volunteer militia companies, 30 US Army soldiers, and 40 US Navy sailors to fight the escaping slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] By about 4 a.m. on January 10, this force had reached Jacques Fortier's plantation, where Hampton thought the escaped slaves had encamped overnight.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] However, the escaped slaves had started back upriver about two hours earlier, had traveled about 15 miles (24 km) back up the coast, and had neared Bernard Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] There, planter Charles Perret, in cooperation with Andry and Judge St.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, had assembled a militia of about 80 men from the river's opposite side.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] At about 9 o'clock, this militia force discovered escaping slaves moving toward high ground on Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret ordered his men to attack the escaping slaves, which he later wrote numbered about 200 men, about half on horseback.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] (Most accounts said only the leaders were mounted, and historians believe it unlikely the escaping men could have gathered so many mounts.) Within a half-hour, 40 to 45 escaping people had been killed; the remainder slipped away into the woods and swamps.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret's and Andry's militias tried to pursue them despite the difficult terrain.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 11, the militia, assisted by Native American trackers as well as hunting dogs, captured Deslondes, whom Andry considered "the principal leader of the bandits." A slave driver and son of a white man and a slave, Deslondes received no trial or interrogation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The following day Pierre Griffee and Hans Wimprenn, who were thought the murderers of M.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] François Trépagnier, were captured, killed, and their heads decapitated for delivery to the Andry estate.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Major Milton and the dragoons from Baton Rouge arrived and provided support for the militia, since Hampton believed them supported by Spanish authorities in West Florida.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Having suppressed the insurrection, the planters and government officials continued to search for people who had escaped.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Those captured later were interrogated and jailed before trials.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Officials convened three tribunals: one at Destrehan Plantation in St.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, and the third in New Orleans (Orleans Parish).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Destrehan trials, overseen by Judge Pierre Bauchet St.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, resulted in the execution of 18 of 21 captured people by firing squad.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some slaves testified against others, but others refused to testify or submit to the all-planter tribunal.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] In New Orleans, Commodore Shaw presumed that "but few of those who have been taken were acquitted." The New Orleans trials resulted in the conviction and summary executions of 11 more slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Three were publicly hanged in the *Place d'Armes*, now Jackson Square.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] One of those spared was a 13-year-old boy, who was ordered to witness another man's death and then received 30 lashes.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Another escaped person was treated with leniency because his uncle turned him in and begged for mercy.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sentence of a third person was commuted because of the valuable information he had given.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heads of those executed were put on pikes and the mutilated bodies of dead rebels displayed to intimidate other slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The naval officer Samuel Hambleton described the heads posted on stakes that lined the levee as follows, "They were brung up here for the sake of their Heads, which decorate our Levee, all the way up the coast.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] U.S. territorial law provided no appeal from a parish court's ruling, even in cases involving imposition of a death sentence on a slave.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] In fact, Claiborne did commute two death sentences, those of Henry and Theodore, each referred by the Orleans Parish court.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] No record has been found of any referral from the court in St.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Charles Parish, or of any refusal by the governor of an application for clemency.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Militias killed about 95 slaves between the battle, subsequent summary apprehensions and executions, as well as by execution after trials.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] From the trial records, most of the leaders appeared to have been mixed-race Creoles or mulattoes, although numerous slaves were native-born Africans.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Fifty-six of the slaves captured on January 10 and involved in the revolt were returned to their masters, who may have punished them but wanted their valuable laborers back to work.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thirty more escaping slaves were captured and returned to their masters after planters determined they had been forced to join the revolt by Deslondes and his men.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heirs of Meuillon petitioned the legislature for permission to free the mulatto slave Bazile, who had worked to preserve his master's plantation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Not all the slaves supported insurrection, knowing the trouble it could bring and not wanting to see their homes and communities destroyed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising was short-lived and quickly crushed by local authorities.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Showing planter influence, the legislature of the Territory of Orleans approved compensation of $300 to planters for each escaping slave killed or executed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The territory gratefully accepted the presence of U.S. troops after the revolt.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The national press covered the insurrection, with some Northerners seeing it arising out of the wrongs suffered under slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration at Norco in January, where they have been joined by some descendants of members of the revolt.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] While the Destrehan Plantation tour concentrates on architecture and white lifestyle and family histories, a small museum in a converted slave cabin (not on the standard tour) features folk paintings of the 1811 uprising.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] More recently, the Whitney Plantation, in St.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, opened in 2014 and is the first plantation museum in the country dedicated to the slave experience.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Whitney Plantation includes a memorial and information to commemorate the 1811 Slave Uprising of the German Coast.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2015, artist Dread Scott began organizing a massive re-enactment of the uprising; the 26 mile, 2-day event took place in November 2019.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising is featured in Talene Monahon's 2020 play about historical reenactment, *How to Load a Musket*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2021, the 1811 Kid Ory Historic House opened on the site of Woodland Plantation in LaPlace, which is in the National Register of Historic Places of the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1811-german-coast-uprising] The museum is dedicated to the German Coast uprising and to Kid Ory, an American jazz composer, trombonist, and bandleader born there in 1886.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] The **1926 Slavery Convention** or the **Convention to Suppress the Slave Trade and Slavery** is an international treaty created under the auspices of the League of Nations and first signed on 25 September 1926.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] It was registered in *League of Nations Treaty Series* on 9 March 1927, the same day it went into effect.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] The objective of the convention is to confirm and advance the suppression of slavery and the slave trade and was extended in 1956 with the Supplementary Convention on the Abolition of Slavery, under the auspices of the United Nations.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] In the Brussels Conference Act of 1890, the signatories "declared that they were equally animated by the firm intention of putting an end to the traffic in African slaves".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] The Red Sea slave trade and slavery in the Arabian Peninsula, and particular the slave trade in Hejaz, attracted attention by the League of Nations and contributed to the creation of the later 1926 Slavery Convention, obliging the British to combat the slave trade in the area.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] The Temporary Slavery Commission (TSC) was appointed by the Council of the League of Nations in June 1924.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] The commission was mixed in composition including former colonial governors such as Frederick Lugard, as well as a representative from Haiti, and a representative from the International Labour Organization.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] The TSC filed their report on 1925 with the recommendation to outlaw the institution of legal chattel slavery and slave trade, which resulted in the 1926 Slavery Convention.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] In 1932 the Committee of Experts on Slavery was established to investigate the efficiency of the 1926 Slavery Convention, which in turn resulted in the establishment of the permanent Advisory Committee of Experts on Slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] The convention established concrete rules and articles to advance the suppression of slavery and the slave trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] As of 2013, there are 99 countries that have signed, acceded to, ratified, succeeded to, or otherwise committed to participation in the conventions as amended, and its subsequent protocol.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] The convention was amended by the protocol entering into force on 7 July 1955.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/1926-slavery-convention] The definition of slavery was further refined and extended by a 1956 Supplementary Convention.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The **harem of the caliphs of the Abbasid Caliphate** (750–1258) in Baghdad was composed of their mothers, wives, slave concubines, female relatives and slave servants (women and eunuchs), occupying a secluded portion of the Abbasid household.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] This institution played an important social function within the Abbasid court and was that part were the women were confined and secluded.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The senior woman in rank in the harem was the mother of the Caliph.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The Abbasid harem acted as a role model for the harems of other Islamic dynasties, as it was during the Abbasid Caliphate that the harem system was fully enforced in the Muslim world.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The harem system first became fully institutionalized in the Islamic world under the Abbasid caliphate.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Although the term *harem* does not denote women's quarters in the Quran, a number of Quranic verses discussing modesty and seclusion were held up by Quranic commentators as religious rationale for the separation of women from men, including the so-called *hijab verse* (33:53).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] In modern usage *hijab* colloquially refers to the religious attire worn by Muslim women, but in this verse it meant "veil" or "curtain" that physically separates female from male space.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Although classical commentators agreed that the verse spoke about a curtain separating the living quarters of Muhammad's wives from visitors to his house, they usually viewed this practice as providing a model for all Muslim women.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] In contrast to the earlier era of the Islamic prophet Muhammad and the Rashidun Caliphate, women in Umayyad and Abbasid society were ideally kept in seclusion and absent from all arenas of the community's central affairs.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The growing seclusion of women were illustrated by the power struggle between the Caliph Al-Hadi and his mother Al-Khayzuran, who refused to live in seclusion but instead challenged the power of the Caliph by giving her own audiences to male supplicants and officials and thus mixing with men.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] 'Who is the better among us, you or me?' asked Caliph al-Hadi of his audience.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] 'Obviously you are the better, Commander of the Faithful,' the assembly replied.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] 'And whose mother is the better, mine or yours?' continued the caliph.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] 'No one likes to have his mother talked about,' responded those present.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Conquests had brought enormous wealth and large numbers of slaves to the Muslim elite.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The majority of the slaves were women and children, many of whom had been dependents or harem-members of the defeated Sassanian upper classes.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] In the wake of the conquests an elite man could potentially own a thousand slaves, and ordinary soldiers could have ten people serving them.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Nabia Abbott, preeminent historian of elite women of the Abbasid Caliphate, describes the lives of harem women as follows.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The marketing of human beings, particularly women, as objects for sexual use meant that elite men owned the vast majority of women they interacted with, and related to them as would masters to slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The Abbasid harem established a model of hierarchy and organisation which was to become a standard for Muslim harems for centuries.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] It was a large institution; during the reign of al-Muqtadir, the harem consisted of 4000 enslaved women and 11.000 enslaved servants.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] On the top of the hierarchy was not the wife of the ruler.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] As a Muslim, the ruler could have several wives, and as he must formally treat them equally, he could not give one wife higher status than another, and give her a role similar to that of a Christian queen consort.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Instead, it was the mother of the Caliph who had the highest rank and position in the harem and thereby among all the women at court.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Her background could be both that of a free wife, or that of an enslaved concubine.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] In the harem resided also the unmarried or divorced daughters, sisters and other nonmarried female relatives of the Caliph.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The Abbasid princesses could make themselves known for their poetry and other accomplishments, as long as they observed the seclusion.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Princess Ulayya bint al-Mahdi only performed in private, chaperoned family functions to avoid any potential impropriety, such as to be compared to the slave-*qiyan*, *jawaris* or *mughanniyat*, but she was referred to as a *qayna* as a tribute to her musical ability.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The wives of the Abbasid caliphs were known as *hurra*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The caliph sometimes entered diplomatic marriages.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] During the later centuries of the Abbasid Caliphate the caliphs often married Seljuk princesses, who acted as pious role models by founding or making donations to pious or charitable institutions.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] It was common for caliphs to manumit and marry their former slave concubines.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Below the legal wives were the enslaved concubines of the caliph.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] These included the *jariya* also known as *ama* and *khadima*, who were often acquired through warfare or slave markets.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] She could be used for sexual relations by him and could also be shared with other men for their pleasure.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The jariya was regarded as property and could be bought, inherited, or freed at the discretion of her owner.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Above the jariyas were the *mahziyyat* or *hazaya*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] These concubines unlike the jariyas could not be shared with other men.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The cost for acquiring a mahziyya could soar to hundreds of thousands of dirhams.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] She often assumed a significant antagonistic role towards the master's wife.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] A slave concubine who was selected to have sex with the caliph and then gave birth to a child by him, attained the coveted position of an *umm al-walad*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] This prevented her from being sold, ensuring she remained a slave under her master's control, and she became freed upon her master's death.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] She could also become a legal wife of the caliph, if he manumitted her and chose to marry her.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The harem also consisted of a large number of jawaris; enslaved female entertainers.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] They performed for the caliph and the rest of the harem.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The Jawari entertainers were not synonymous with the concubines, and the jawaris and concubines belonged to two different categories.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] However, the Jawaris could be chosen by the Caliph for sexual intercourse, and thus transition to become a concubine.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The jawaris were sometimes former *qiyan*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] One famous harem entertainer was the concubine ʽInān and the singer Shāriyah.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] 809–813) in Baghdad, there was a category of female entertainers known as *ghulamyyat*, slave-girls dressed as boys, who were trained to perform as singers and musicians and who attended the drinking parties of the sovereign and his male guests.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The *qahramana* (Arabic: قَهْرَمانَة *qahramānah*, 'stewardess') were female slaves responsible for various tasks within the harem.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] They could act as governesses for the children, as well as the personal servants and agents of the women, functioning as intermediaries between the harem women and the outside world.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The qahramana were the only women who were allowed the mobility to leave and enter the harem, and they regularly left the harem to make purchases for the secluded harem women and handle the affairs between the women and the merchants and tradespeople of the outside world.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] This mobility was envied by the harem women, and one story describe the envy of a harem woman, who wished to become a qahramana so that she would be able to leave the harem, and finally managed to achieve her goal to become a qahramana.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The mobility of a qahramana made them into influential figures as the personal agents and messengers between the harem women and the world outside the harem.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Umm Musa, qahramana to the mother of al-Muqtadir, became an influential figure as a messenger of supplicants to the Caliph mother and the Caliph.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The perhaps most famous of them all were Thumal the Qahraman.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The eunuchs were the castrated male slaves responsible for guarding the harem, for preventing the women from leaving the harem and for approving any visitor before they gained entrance.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The custom of using eunuchs as servants for women inside the Islamic harems had a preceding example in the life of Muhammad himself, who used the eunuch Mabur as a servant in the house of his own slave concubine Maria al-Qibtiyya; both of them slaves from Egypt.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] During the Abbasid period, eunuchs became a permanent institution inside the Islamic harems after the model of the Abbasid harem.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] With the exception of the legal wives and female relatives of the Caliph, the inhabitants of the harem—concubines, entertainers and eunuchs—were all enslaved people.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The slaves were either war captives (called *sabaya*) or bought from slave markets, and the slave women were divided in to the categories *jawari* and *qiyan* (singers), *mahziyyat* (concubines) and *qahramanat* (stewardesses).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The men meant for the harem were all eunuchs; the non eunuch males served the palace outside of the harem.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] According to Islamic practice of slavery and slave trade, foreign non-Muslims were free to enslave, and it was preferred that slaves were to be non-Muslims from non-Muslim regions.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] In accordance with the *Ma malakat aymanukum*, the principle of concubinage, women could be legally kept as concubines in the harem if they were of non-Muslim origin.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The four main ways to enslave a person were by kidnapping, by slave raids, by piracy, or by buying a child from poor parents.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Since many parts of Persia remained Zoroastrian the first centuries after conquest, some non-Muslim "infidel territory" in Persia were also exposed to Muslim slave raids, particularly Daylam in northwestern Iran and the Pagan mountainous region of Ḡūr in central Afghanistan.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] Two of the twelve caliphs’ mothers whose nationalities are known were European saqaliba; Al-Musta'in's mother Mukhariq, and Al-Mu'tazz's mother Qabiha.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] When the Mongols of the Ilkhanate conquered Baghdad in 1258, they took an inventory of the possessions of Caliph al-Musta'sim.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] This included the inhabitants of his harem.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The inventory proved that the Abbasid harem at that point contained 1000 eunuchs and 700 women, whom the Caliph claimed had never seen sun nor moon.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The Caliph asked to keep the women, and was allowed to select 100 to keep.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] "An order was given for the Caliph's harem to be counted.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] There were seven hundred women and concubines and a thousand servants.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The Caliph was however killed shortly after, and the members of his household and his family where killed or taken captive as slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] “They swept through the city like hungry falcons attacking a flight of doves, or like raging wolves attacking sheep, with loose reins and shameless faces, murdering and spreading terror...beds and cushions made of gold and encrusted with jewels were cut to pieces with knives and torn to shreds.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abbasid-harem] The harem system was similar during the Ottoman Empire, with only minor changes in the model of the Imperial Harem.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In the 17th and early 18th centuries, English Quakers and a few evangelical religious groups condemned slavery (by then applied mostly to Africans) as un-Christian.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] A few secular thinkers of the Enlightenment criticised it for violating the rights of man.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] James Edward Oglethorpe was the first to act on the Enlightenment case against slavery on humanistic grounds.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In his "Georgia Experiment" he convinced Parliament to ban slavery in his Province of Georgia from 1735.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] However, slavery was reinstated in 1751.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] He also encouraged his friends Granville Sharp, who founded the Society for the Abolition of the Slave Trade, and Hannah More to pursue the cause vigorously.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Soon after his death in 1785, they joined with William Wilberforce and others in forming the Clapham Sect.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The slave trade had been banned in England in 1102, by the Church Council of London, convened by Anselm.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] However, the council had no legislative powers, unless decreed and signed by the monarch.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In Cartwright's Case of 1569 regarding the punishment of a slave from Russia, the court ruled that English law could not recognise slavery, as it was never established officially.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] This ruling was overshadowed by later developments.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] It was upheld in 1700 by Lord Chief Justice Sir John Holt when he ruled that "As soon as a man sets foot on English ground he is free".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] English colonists imported slaves to the North American colonies and by the 18th century, traders began to import slaves from Africa, India and East Asia (where they were trading) to London and Edinburgh to work as servants.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Men who migrated to the North American colonies often took their East Indian slaves or servants with them, as East Indians have been documented in colonial records.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Some of the first freedom suits, court cases in Britain to challenge the legality of slavery, took place in Scotland in 1755 and 1769.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Each of the slaves had been baptised in Scotland and challenged the legality of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] They set the precedent of legal procedure in British courts that would later lead to success for the plaintiffs.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In these cases, deaths of the plaintiff and defendant, respectively, brought an end to the action before a court decision could be rendered.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] African slaves were not bought or sold in London but were brought by masters from other places.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Together with people from other nations, especially non-Christian ones, Africans were considered foreigners and thus ineligible to be English subjects; England had no naturalisation procedure.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The African slaves' legal status was unclear until Somersett's Case in 1772, when the fugitive slave James Somersett forced a decision by the courts.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Somersett had escaped and his master, Charles Steuart, had him captured and imprisoned on board a ship, intending to ship him to Jamaica to be resold into slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] While in London, Somersett had been baptised and three godparents issued a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] As a result, Lord Mansfield, Chief Justice of the Court of the King's Bench, had to judge whether Somersett's abduction was lawful or not under English Common Law.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] No legislation had ever been passed to establish slavery in England.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The case received national attention and five advocates supported the action on behalf of Somersett.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Although the legal implications of the judgement are unclear when analysed by lawyers, the judgement was generally taken at the time to have determined that slavery did not exist under English common law and was thus prohibited in England.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] By 1774, between 10,000 and 15,000 slaves gained freedom in England.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The decision did not apply to British overseas territories; e.g. the American colonies had established slavery by positive laws.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Somersett's case became a significant part of the common law of slavery in the English-speaking world and it helped launch the movement to abolish slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] After reading about Somersett's Case, Joseph Knight, an enslaved African who had been purchased by his master John Wedderburn in Jamaica and brought to Scotland, left him.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Married and with a child, he filed a freedom suit, on the grounds that he could not be held as a slave in Great Britain.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Wedderburn* (1778), Wedderburn said that Knight owed him "perpetual servitude".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The Court of Session of Scotland ruled against him, saying that chattel slavery was not recognised under the law of Scotland and slaves could seek court protection to leave a master or avoid being forcibly removed from Scotland to be returned to slavery in the colonies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] At this point the plantocracy became concerned, and got organised, setting up the London Society of West India Planters and Merchants to represent their views.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] From its inception in 1780, the organisation played a major role in resisting the abolition of the slave trade and that of slavery itself.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The Society brought together three different groups: British sugar merchants, absentee planters and colonial agents.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Writing critically of English altruism in abolishing the slave trade, African-American historian W.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Antislavery sentiment may have grown in the British Isles in the first few years after the *Somersett* case.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In 1774, influenced by the case and by the writings of Quaker abolitionist Anthony Benezet, John Wesley, the leader of the Methodist tendency in the Church of England, published *Thoughts Upon Slavery*, in which he passionately criticised the practice.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Despite the ending of slavery in Great Britain, the West Indian colonies of the British Empire continued to practice it.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] British banks continued to finance the commodities and shipping industries in the colonies they had earlier established which still relied upon slavery, despite the legal developments in Great Britain.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Cowper was a close friend of John Newton, who had been involved in the slave trade during his naval career.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In later life, following his conversion to Christianity, and his ordination in the Church of England, Newton was an active abolitionist.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] He described slavery as a "stain on our National character." One important contribution by Newton to the abolition of slavery was his influence on William Wilberforce.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Newton convinced Wilberforce that he would achieve more by remaining in Parliament than by becoming a priest in the Church of England.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In 1783, an anti-slavery movement began in Britain.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] That year a group of Quakers founded their first abolitionist organisation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The Quakers continued to be influential throughout the lifetime of the movement, in many ways leading the campaign.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] On 17 June 1783, Sir Cecil Wray (one of the Members of Parliament for Westminster) presented the Quaker petition to parliament.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Also in 1783, Beilby Porteus, Bishop of Chester, issued a call to the Church of England to cease its involvement in the slave trade and to formulate a policy to improve the conditions of Afro-Caribbean slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The exploration of the African continent by such British groups as the African Association (1788) promoted the abolitionists' cause.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Such expeditions highlighted the sophistication of African social organisation; before this, Europeans had considered them 'other' and uncivilised.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The African Association had close ties with William Wilberforce, who became known as a prominent figure in the campaign for abolition in the British Empire.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Africans themselves played a visible role in the abolition movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In Britain, Olaudah Equiano, whose autobiography was published in nine editions in his lifetime, campaigned tirelessly against the slave trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Also important were horrific images such as the famous Wedgwood anti-slavery medallion of 1787 and the engraving showing the ghastly layout of the slave ship, the *Brookes*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] After the formation of the Committee for the Abolition of the Slave Trade in 1787, William Wilberforce led the cause of abolition through the parliamentary campaign.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] It finally abolished the slave trade in the British Empire with the Slave Trade Act 1807.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] He continued to campaign for the abolition of slavery in the British Empire, which he lived to see in the Slavery Abolition Act 1833.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In 1787, Thomas Clarkson, Granville Sharp, and other abolitionists founded the Society for the Abolition of the Slave Trade, considering the termination of the transatlantic slave trade a necessary precursor to the complete abolition of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] There traders sold or exchanged the slaves for rum and sugar (in the Caribbean) and tobacco and rice (in the American South), which they took back to British ports.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The merchants traded in three places with each round-trip.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Political influence against the inhumanity of the slave trade grew strongly in the late 18th century.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Europeans and Africans worked for abolition of the slave trade and slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Quakers made up most of the Committee for the Abolition of the Slave Trade and were the first to present a petition against the slave trade to the British Parliament.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] As Dissenters, Quakers were not eligible to become British MPs in the late 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The Anglican evangelist William Wilberforce led the parliamentary campaign.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Clarkson became the group's most prominent researcher, gathering vast amounts of data and gaining first-hand accounts by interviewing sailors and former slaves at British ports such as Bristol, Liverpool and London.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Clarkson trailed the country setting up a network of 1,200 local abolition groups.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] They campaigned through public meetings and the publication of pamphlets and petitions, a petition in 1792 got 400,000 signatures and the petition in 1814 got 1,375,000 signatures.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] One of the earliest books promoted by Clarkson and the Committee for the Abolition of the Slave Trade was the autobiography of the freed slave Olaudah Equiano.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The movement had support from such freed slaves, from many denominational groups such as Swedenborgians, Quakers, Baptists, Methodists and others.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] They reached out for support from the new industrial workers of the cities in the Midlands and north of England.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Even women and children, previously un-politicised groups, became involved in the campaign especially the successful sugar boycott.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] At this time, women often had to hold separate meetings as there were social rules against their appearing in public meetings.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] They could not vote, nor could the majority of the men in Britain at the time.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In 1792, after multiple petitions had been presented, the House of Commons voted in favour of the gradual abolition of the slave trade, a decision subsequently reversed by the House of Lords, which wanted to hear its own evidence for and against the trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The abolitionists negotiated with chieftains in West Africa to purchase land to establish 'Freetown' – a settlement for former slaves of the British Empire (the Poor Blacks of London) and the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Great Britain had promised freedom to American slaves who left rebel owners to join its cause during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] It evacuated thousands of slaves together with its troops and transported 3,000 Black Loyalists to Nova Scotia for resettlement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] About a decade later, they were offered a chance to resettle in Freetown and several hundred made the move.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Freetown was the first settlement of the colony of Sierra Leone, which was protected under a British act of Parliament in 1807–08.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] British influence in West Africa grew through a series of negotiations with local chieftains to end trading in slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] These included agreements to permit British navy ships to intercept chieftains' ships to ensure their merchants were not carrying slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Also from 1800 the Royal African Corps was recruited from West African volunteers, and eventually included freed slaves from the Caribbean before it was disbanded in 1819.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In 1796, John Gabriel Stedman published the memoirs of his five-year voyage to the Dutch-controlled Surinam in South America as part of a military force sent out to subdue bosnegers, former slaves living in the interior.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The book is critical of the treatment of slaves and contains many images by William Blake and Francesco Bartolozzi depicting the cruel treatment of runaway slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] It was an example of what became a large body of abolitionist literature.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The Slave Trade Act was passed by the British Parliament on 25 March 1807, making the slave trade illegal throughout the British Empire.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] It was partly enforced by the West Africa Squadron.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The Act imposed a fine of £100 for every slave found aboard a British ship.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The 1807 act's intention was to entirely outlaw the slave trade within the British Empire, but the lucrative trade continued through smuggling.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Sometimes captains at risk of being caught by the Royal Navy would throw slaves into the sea to reduce their fines.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Abolitionist Henry Brougham realized that trading would continue, and so as a new MP successfully introduced the Slave Trade Felony Act 1811.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] This law at last made slave trading a criminal felony throughout the empire, and for British subjects worldwide.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] This proved far more effective and ended the trade across the Empire, as the Royal Navy ruthlessly pursued slave ships.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In 1827, Britain defined participation in the slave trade as piracy and punishable by death.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Between 1808 and 1860, the Royal Navy's West Africa Squadron seized approximately 1,600 slave ships and freed 150,000 Africans who were aboard.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Britain used its influence to coerce other countries to agree to treaties to end their slave trade and allow the Royal Navy to seize their slave ships.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Action was also taken against African leaders who refused to agree to British treaties to outlaw the trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] For example, the 1851 Reduction of Lagos deposed "the usurping King of Lagos".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Britain signed anti-slavery treaties with more than 50 African rulers.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] After the Slave Trade Act 1807, slaves could still be held, though not sold, within the British Empire.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In the 1820s, the abolitionist movement may have revived the campaign against the institution of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In 1823 the first Anti-Slavery Society was founded in Britain.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The society's members consisted of a union of non-conformist churches and many had previously campaigned against the slave trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In 1831, enslaved man Sam Sharpe led the Christmas Rebellion (Baptist War) in Jamaica, an event that catalyzed anti-slavery sentiment.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] This combination of political pressure and popular uprisings convinced the British government that there was no longer any middle ground between slavery and emancipation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] On 28 August 1833, the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 received royal assent, paving the way for the abolition of slavery within the British Empire and its colonies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The apprenticeship system was deeply unpopular with slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] On 1 August 1834, as the Governor in Port of Spain, Trinidad addressed an audience about the new laws, the mostly elderly, unarmed slaves began chanting: "Pas de six ans.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Peaceful protests continued until the government passed a resolution to abolish apprenticeship and the slaves gained *de facto* freedom.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Full emancipation for all slaves was legally granted on 1 August 1838, ahead of schedule, making Trinidad the first British slave society to fully end slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The government set aside £20 million for compensation of slave owners for their "property" across the Empire, but it did not offer former slaves compensation or reparations.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] This was because abolitionists had not planned for much more than the long-awaited reform of the law, and felt that freedom along with the option of returning to Africa to live in Freetown, or the nearby state of Liberia, was infinitely preferable to continued chattel slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In context, the £20 million voted by Parliament to compensate slave owners under the 1833 Act can be compared with the Gross Domestic Product of the UK in 1832, which was £443 million and government spending which was £51.5m.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] In 1839, the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society was formed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] At the time, Britain continued to import cotton and other commodities from the U.S.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Deep South, which relied on slavery for cotton production, to fuel the spinning and weaving mills in Manchester and other northern cities.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The finished goods furnished Britain's low-wage export manufacturing economy, with surpluses exported to Europe and India.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] London merchant banks made loans throughout the supply chain to planters, factors, warehousers, carters, shippers, spinners, weavers, and exporters.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society campaigned to outlaw slavery in other countries, and pressured the British government to do more to enforce the suppression of the slave trade, by declaring slave traders to be pirates and pursuing them as such.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The Society is in operation today as Anti-Slavery International, the world's oldest international human rights organisation, with its headquarters in London.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] On 20 December 1841, the first multilateral treaty for the suppression of the slave trade, the Treaty for the Suppression of the African Slave Trade, was signed in London by the representatives of Austria, Britain, France, Prussia, and Russia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] There was a treaty between Britain and the United States of America in 1862.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] The Slave Trade Department was established in 1841, and was headed by the first superintendent, James Bandinel.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] It came to inherit its own staffing budget in 1841, and in 1854 it was finally recognised as a branch of the Foreign Office.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-kingdom] Arguably, its alignment with the Foreign Office was "a tacit of acknowledgement that suppression was a gradual process, but revolution was imminent".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The anti-slavery movement originated during the Age of Enlightenment, focused on ending the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In Colonial America, a few German Quakers issued the 1688 Germantown Quaker Petition Against Slavery, which marked the beginning of the American abolitionist movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the Revolutionary War, evangelical colonists were the primary advocates for the opposition to slavery and the slave trade, doing so on the basis of humanitarian ethics.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Still, others such as James Oglethorpe, the founder of the colony of Georgia, also retained political motivations for the removal of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Prohibiting slavery through the 1735 Georgia Experiment in part to prevent Spanish partnership with Georgia's runaway slaves, Oglethorpe eventually revoked the act in 1750 after the Spanish's defeat in the Battle of Bloody Marsh eight years prior.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] During the Revolutionary era, all states abolished the international slave trade, but South Carolina reversed its decision.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Between the Revolutionary War and 1804, laws, constitutions, or court decisions in each of the Northern states provided for the gradual or immediate abolition of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] No Southern state adopted similar policies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1807, Congress made the importation of slaves a crime, effective January 1, 1808, which was as soon as Article I, section 9 of the Constitution allowed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A small but dedicated group, under leaders such as William Lloyd Garrison and Frederick Douglass, agitated for abolition in the mid-19th century.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown became an advocate and militia leader in attempting to end slavery by force of arms.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Civil War, immediate emancipation became a war goal for the Union in 1863 and was fully achieved in 1865.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionism began well before the United States was founded as a nation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1652, Rhode Island made it illegal for any person, black or white, to be "bound" longer than ten years.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The law, however, was widely ignored, and Rhode Island became involved in the slave trade in 1700.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] An early prominent example of resistance by enslaved people occurred during Bacon's Rebellion in 1676.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Occurring in Virginia, the rebellion saw European indentured servants and African people (of indentured, enslaved, and free negroes) band together against William Berkeley because of his refusal to fully remove Native American tribes in the region.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At the time, Native Americans in the region were hosting raids against lower-class settlers encroaching on their land after the Third Powhatan War (1644–1646), which left many white and black indentured servants and slaves without a sense of protection from their government.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Led by Nathaniel Bacon, the unification that occurred between the white lower class and blacks during this rebellion was perceived as dangerous and thus was quashed with the implementation of the Virginia Slave Codes of 1705.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Still, this event introduced the premise that blacks and whites could work together towards the goal of self-liberation, which became increasingly prevalent as abolition gained traction within America.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first written statement against slavery in Colonial America was prepared in 1688 by members of the Religious Society of Friends.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The intention of the petition was to stop slavery within the Quaker community, where 70% of Quakers owned slaves between 1681 and 1705.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It acknowledged the universal rights of all people.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While the Quaker establishment did not take action at that time, the unusually early, clear, and forceful argument in the petition initiated the spirit that finally led to the end of slavery in the Society of Friends (1776) and in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania (1780).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Quaker Quarterly Meeting of Chester, Pennsylvania, made its first protest in 1711.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Within a few decades the entire slave trade was under attack, being opposed by such Quaker leaders as William Burling, Benjamin Lay, Ralph Sandiford, William Southby, John Woolman, and Anthony Benezet.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Benezet was particularly influential, inspiring a later generation of notable anti-slavery activists, including Granville Sharp, John Wesley, Thomas Clarkson, Olaudah Equiano, Benjamin Franklin, Benjamin Rush, Absalom Jones, and Bishop Richard Allen, among others.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Samuel Sewall, a prominent Bostonian, wrote *The Selling of Joseph* (1700) in protest of the widening practice of outright slavery as opposed to indentured servitude in the colonies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This is the earliest-recorded anti-slavery tract published in the future United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slavery was banned in the colony of Georgia soon after its founding in 1733.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The colony's founder, James Edward Oglethorpe, fended off repeated attempts by South Carolina merchants and land speculators to introduce slavery into the colony.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His motivations included tactical defense against Spanish collusion with runaway slaves, and prevention of Georgia's largely reformed criminal population from replicating South Carolina's planter class structure.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1737, Quaker abolitionist Benjamin Lay published *All Slave-Keepers That Keep the Innocent in Bondage, Apostates*, which was printed by his friend, Benjamin Franklin.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The event resulted in 25 colonists and 35 to 50 African slaves killed, as well as the implementation of the 1740 Negro Act to prevent another slave uprising.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In her book, "The Slave's Cause" by Manisha Sinha, Sinha considers the Stono Rebellion to be an important act of abolition from the perspective of the slave, recognizing their agency and subsequent humanity as cause for self-liberation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The struggle between Georgia and South Carolina led to the first debates in Parliament over the issue of slavery, occurring between 1740 and 1742.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Rhode Island Quakers, associated with Moses Brown, were among the first in America to free slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Benjamin Rush was another leader, as were many Quakers.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Woolman gave up most of his business in 1756 to devote himself to campaigning against slavery along with other Quakers.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Between 1764 and 1774, seventeen enslaved African Americans appeared before the Massachusetts courts in freedom suits, spurred on the decision made in the *Somerset v.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Stewart* case, which although not applying the colonies was still received positively by American abolitionists.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Boston lawyer Benjamin Kent represented them.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Whipple*) to liberate Jenny Slew, a mixed-race woman who had been kidnapped in Massachusetts and then handled as a slave.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to historian Steven Pincus, many of the colonial legislatures worked to enact laws that would limit slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Provincial legislature of Massachusetts Bay, as noted by historian Gary B.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nash, approved a law "prohibiting the importation and purchase of slaves by any Massachusetts citizen." The Loyalist governor of Massachusetts, Thomas Hutchinson, vetoed the law, an action that prompted angered reaction from the general public.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionists were cheered by the decision in *Somerset v Stewart* (1772), which prohibited slavery in the United Kingdom, though not in its colonies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1774, the influential Fairfax Resolves called for an end to the "wicked, cruel and unnatural" Atlantic slave trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] One of the first articles advocating the emancipation of slaves and the abolition of slavery was written by Thomas Paine.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Titled "African Slavery in America", it appeared on 8 March 1775 in the *Postscript to the Pennsylvania Journal and Weekly Advertiser*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Society for the Relief of Free Negroes Unlawfully Held in Bondage (Pennsylvania Abolition Society) was the first American abolition society, formed 14 April 1775, in Philadelphia, primarily by Quakers.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The society suspended operations during the American Revolutionary War and was reorganized in 1784, with Benjamin Franklin as its first president.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1777, the Vermont Republic became the first independent state in North America to prohibit slavery: slaves were not directly freed, but masters were required to remove slaves from Vermont.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Constitution included several provisions which accommodated slavery, although none used the word.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Passed unanimously by the Congress of the Confederation in 1787, the Northwest Ordinance forbade slavery in the Northwest Territory, a vast area (the future Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, and Wisconsin) in which slavery had been legal, but population was sparse.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to begin a gradual abolition of slavery was Pennsylvania, in 1780.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All importation of slaves was prohibited, but none were freed at first, only the slaves of masters who failed to register them with the state, along with the "future children" of enslaved mothers.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Those enslaved in Pennsylvania before the 1780 law went into effect were not freed until 1847.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Massachusetts took a much more radical position.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1780, during the Revolution, Massachusetts ratified its constitution and included within it a clause that declared all men equal.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Based upon this clause, several freedom suits were filed by enslaved African Americans living in Massachusetts.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1783, its Supreme Court, in the case of *Commonwealth v.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nathaniel Jennison*, reaffirmed the case of *Brom and Bett v.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Ashley*, which held that even slaves were people who had a constitutional right to liberty.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This gave freedom to slaves, effectively abolishing slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] States with a greater economic interest in slaves, such as New York and New Jersey, passed gradual emancipation laws.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While some of these laws were gradual, these states enacted the first abolition laws in the entire "New World".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the State of New York, the enslaved population was transformed into indentured servants before being granted full emancipation in 1827.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In other states, abolitionist legislation provided freedom only for the children of the enslaved.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In New Jersey, slavery was not fully prohibited until the passage of the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All of the other states north of Maryland began gradual abolition of slavery between 1781 and 1804, based on the Pennsylvania model and by 1804, all the Northern states had passed laws to gradually or immediately abolish it.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some slaves continued in involuntary, unpaid "indentured servitude" for two more decades, and others were moved south and sold to new owners in slave states.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some individual slaveholders, particularly in the upper South, freed slaves, sometimes in their wills.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many noted they had been moved by the revolutionary ideals of the equality of men.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The number of free blacks as a proportion of the black population in the upper South increased from less than 1 percent to nearly 10 percent between 1790 and 1810 as a result of these actions.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some slave owners, concerned about the increase in free blacks, which they viewed as destabilizing, freed slaves on condition that they emigrate to Africa.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All U.S. states abolished the transatlantic slave trade by 1798.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] South Carolina, which had abolished the slave trade in 1787, reversed that decision in 1803.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the American South, freedom suits were rejected by the courts, which held that the rights in the state constitutions did not apply to African Americans.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The institution of slavery remained solid in the South, and that region's customs and social beliefs evolved into a strident defense of slavery in response to the rise of a growing anti-slavery stance in the North.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1835 alone, abolitionists mailed over a million pieces of anti-slavery literature to the South, giving rise to the gag rules in Congress, after the theft of mail from the Charleston, South Carolina, post office, and much back-and-forth about whether postmasters were required to deliver this mail.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Postmaster General, they were not.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Under the Constitution, the importation of enslaved persons could not be prohibited until 1808 (20 years).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] As the end of the 20 years approached, an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves sailed through Congress with little opposition.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] President Jefferson signed it, and it went effect on January 1, 1808.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1820, the Act to Protect the Commerce of the United States and Punish the Crime of Piracy was passed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This law made importing slaves into the United States a death penalty offense.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1830, most Americans were, at least in principle, opposed to slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, opponents of slavery deliberated on how to end the institution, as well as what would become of the slaves once they were free.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1830s there was a progressive shift in thinking in the North.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Mainstream opinion changed from gradual emancipation and resettlement of freed blacks in Africa, sometimes a condition of their manumission, to immediatism: freeing all the slaves immediately and sorting out the problems later.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This change was in many cases sudden, a consequence of the individual's coming in direct contact with the horrors of American slavery, or hearing of them from a credible source.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American beginning of abolitionism as a political movement is usually dated from 1 January 1831, when Wm.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lloyd Garrison (as he always signed himself) published the first issue of his new weekly newspaper, *The Liberator* (1831), which appeared without interruption until slavery in the United States was abolished in 1865, when it closed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists included those who joined the American Anti-Slavery Society or its auxiliary groups in the 1830s and 1840s, as the movement fragmented.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The fragmented anti-slavery movement included groups such as the Liberty Party; the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society; the American Missionary Association; and the Church Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Historians traditionally distinguish between moderate anti-slavery reformers or gradualists, who concentrated on stopping the spread of slavery, and radical abolitionists or immediatists, whose demands for unconditional emancipation often merged with a concern for Black civil rights.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nearly all Northern politicians, such as Abraham Lincoln, rejected the "immediate emancipation" called for by the abolitionists, seeing it as "extreme".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Indeed, many Northern leaders, including Lincoln, Stephen Douglas (the Democratic nominee in 1860), John C.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Frémont (the Republican nominee in 1856), and Ulysses S.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Grant married into slave-owning Southern families without any moral qualms.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Anti-slavery as a principle was far more than just the wish to prevent the expansion of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] After 1840, abolitionists rejected this because it let sin continue to exist; they demanded that slavery end everywhere, immediately and completely.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown was the only abolitionist to have actually planned a violent insurrection, though David Walker promoted the idea.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The abolitionist movement was strengthened by the activities of free African Americans, especially in the Black church, who argued that the old Biblical justifications for slavery contradicted the New Testament.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] African-American activists and their writings were rarely heard outside the Black community.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, they were tremendously influential on a few sympathetic white people, most prominently the first white activist to reach prominence, Wm.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lloyd Garrison, who was its most effective propagandist.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Garrison's efforts to recruit eloquent spokesmen led to the discovery of ex-slave Frederick Douglass, who eventually became a prominent activist in his own right.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Eventually, Douglass would publish his own widely distributed abolitionist newspaper, *North Star*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1850s, the American abolitionist movement split into two camps over the question of whether the United States Constitution did or did not protect slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This issue arose in the late 1840s after the publication of *The Unconstitutionality of Slavery* by Lysander Spooner.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Garrisonians, led by Garrison and Wendell Phillips, publicly burned copies of the Constitution, called it a pact with slavery, and demanded its abolition and replacement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another camp, led by Lysander Spooner, Gerrit Smith, and eventually Douglass, considered the Constitution to be an anti-slavery document.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Using an argument based upon Natural Law and a form of social contract theory, they said that slavery fell outside the Constitution's scope of legitimate authority and therefore should be abolished.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another split in the abolitionist movement was along class lines.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The artisan republicanism of Robert Dale Owen and Frances Wright stood in stark contrast to the politics of prominent elite abolitionists such as industrialist Arthur Tappan and his evangelist brother Lewis.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While the former pair opposed slavery on a basis of solidarity of "wage slaves" with "chattel slaves", the Whiggish Tappans strongly rejected this view, opposing the characterization of Northern workers as "slaves" in any sense.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many American abolitionists took an active role in opposing slavery by supporting the Underground Railroad.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was made illegal by the federal Fugitive Slave Law of 1850, arguably the most hated and most openly evaded federal legislation in the nation's history.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nevertheless, participants like Harriet Tubman, Henry Highland Garnet, Alexander Crummell, Amos Noë Freeman, and others continued with their work.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists were particularly active in Ohio, where some worked directly in the Underground Railroad.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Since only the Ohio River separated free Ohio from slave Kentucky, it was a popular destination for fugitive slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Supporters helped them there, in many cases to cross Lake Erie by boat, into Canada.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Western Reserve area of northeast Ohio was "probably the most intensely antislavery section of the country." The Oberlin-Wellington Rescue got national publicity.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionist John Brown grew up in Hudson, Ohio.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the South, members of the abolitionist movement or other people opposing slavery were often targets of lynch mob violence before the American Civil War.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His fellow Duffield Street residents Thomas and Harriet Truesdell were leading members of the abolitionist movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Truesdell was a founding member of the Providence Anti-slavery Society before moving to Brooklyn in 1838.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Harriet Truesdell was also very active in the movement, organizing an anti-slavery convention in Pennsylvania Hall (Philadelphia).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another prominent Brooklyn-based abolitionist was Rev.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Joshua Leavitt, trained as a lawyer at Yale, who stopped practicing law in order to attend Yale Divinity School, and subsequently edited the abolitionist newspaper *The Emancipator* and campaigned against slavery, as well as advocating other social reforms.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1841, Leavitt published *The Financial Power of Slavery*, which argued that the South was draining the national economy due to its reliance on enslaved workers.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2007, Duffield Street was given the name Abolitionist Place, and the Truesdells' home at 227 Duffield received landmark status in 2021.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was a direct result of the Union victory in the American Civil War.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The central issue of the war was slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the North, most opponents of slavery supported other modernizing reform movements such as the temperance movement, public schooling, and prison- and asylum-building.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They were split on the issue of women's activism and their political role, and this contributed to a major rift in the Society.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1839, brothers Arthur Tappan and Lewis Tappan left the Society and formed the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society, which did not admit women.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Other members of the Society, including Charles Turner Torrey, Amos Phelps, Henry Stanton, and Alanson St.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Clair, in addition to disagreeing with Garrison on the women's issue, urged taking a much more activist approach to abolitionism and consequently challenged Garrison's leadership at the Society's annual meeting in January 1839.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] When the challenge was beaten back, they left and founded the New Organization, which adopted a more activist approach to freeing slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Soon after, in 1840, they formed the Liberty Party, which had as its sole platform the abolition of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1840, Garrison himself announced the formation of a third new organization, the Friends of Universal Reform, with sponsors and founding members including prominent reformers Maria Chapman, Abby Kelley Foster, Oliver Johnson, and Bronson Alcott (father of Louisa May Alcott).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists such as William Lloyd Garrison repeatedly condemned slavery for contradicting the principles of freedom and equality on which the country was founded.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The most influential abolitionist publication was *Uncle Tom's Cabin* (1852), the best-selling novel by Harriet Beecher Stowe, who had attended the anti-slavery debates at Lane, of which her father, Lyman Beecher, was the president.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Outraged by the Fugitive Slave Law of 1850 (which made the escape narrative part of everyday news), Stowe emphasized the horrors that abolitionists had long claimed about slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Her depiction of the evil slave owner Simon Legree, a transplanted Yankee who kills the Christ-like Uncle Tom, outraged the North, helped sway British public opinion against the South, and inflamed Southern slave owners who tried to refute it by showing that some slave owners were humanitarian.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It inspired numerous anti-Tom, pro-slavery novels, several written and published by women.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to a book reviewer, "Next to *Uncle Tom's Cabin* (1852), Hinton Helper's critique of slavery and the Southern class system, *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857), was arguably the most important antislavery book of the 1850s." According to historian George M.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Two diametrically opposed anti-slavery positions emerged regarding the United States Constitution.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Garrisonians emphasized that the document permitted and protected slavery and was therefore "an agreement with hell" that had to be rejected in favor of immediate emancipation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The mainstream anti-slavery position adopted by the new Republican party argued that the Constitution could and should be used to eventually end slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They assumed that the Constitution gave the government no authority to abolish slavery directly.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, there were multiple tactics available to support the long-term strategy of using the Constitution as a battering ram against the peculiar institution.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] First Congress could block the admission of any new slave states.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] That would steadily move the balance of power in Congress and the Electoral College in favor of freedom.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could abolish slavery in the District of Columbia and the territories.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could use the Commerce Clause to end the interstate slave trade, thereby crippling the steady movement of slavery from the southeast to the southwest.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could recognize free blacks as full citizens and insist on due process rights to protect fugitive slaves from being captured and returned to bondage.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Finally, the government could use patronage powers to promote the anti-slavery cause across the country, especially in the border states.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Pro-slavery elements considered the Republican strategy to be much more dangerous to their cause than radical abolitionism.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lincoln's election was met by secession.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Indeed, the Republican strategy mapped the "crooked path to abolition" that prevailed during the Civil War.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1850s, the slave trade remained legal in all 16 states of the American South.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While slavery was fading away in the cities and border states, it remained strong in plantation areas that grew cash crops such as cotton, sugar, rice, tobacco or hemp.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1860 United States census, the slave population in the United States had grown to four million.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionism, after Nat Turner's revolt ended its discussion in the South, was based in the North, and white Southerners alleged it fostered slave rebellion.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The white abolitionist movement in the North was led by social reformers, especially William Lloyd Garrison, founder of the American Anti-Slavery Society, and writers such as John Greenleaf Whittier and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Black activists included former slaves such as Frederick Douglass, and free blacks such as the brothers Charles Henry Langston and John Mercer Langston, who helped to found the Ohio Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some abolitionists said that slavery was criminal and a sin; they also criticized slave owners for using black women as concubines and taking sexual advantage of them.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Compromise of 1850 attempted to resolve issues surrounding slavery caused by the War with Mexico and the admission to the Union of the slave Republic of Texas.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Compromise of 1850 was proposed by "The Great Compromiser" Henry Clay; support was coordinated by Senator Stephen A.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fugitive Slave Law was a concession to the South.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists were outraged, because the new law required Northerners to help in the capture and return of runaway slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1854, Congress passed the Kansas–Nebraska Act, which opened those territories to slavery if the local residents voted that way.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The anti-slavery gains made in previous compromises were reversed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A firestorm of outrage brought together former Whigs, Know-Nothings, and former Free Soil Democrats to form a new party in 1854–56, the Republican Party.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It included a program of rapid modernization involving the government promotion of industry, railroads, banks, free homesteads, and colleges, all to the annoyance of the South.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The new party denounced the Slave Power – that is the political power of the slave owners who supposedly controlled the national government for their own benefit and to the disadvantage of the ordinary white man.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republicans wanted to achieve the gradual extinction of slavery by market forces, because its members believed that free labor was superior to slave labor.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Southern leaders said the Republican policy of blocking the expansion of slavery into the West made them second-class citizens, and challenged their autonomy.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] With the 1860 presidential victory of Abraham Lincoln, seven Deep South states whose economy was based on cotton and slavery decided to secede and form a new nation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Civil War broke out in April 1861 with the firing on Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] When Lincoln called for troops to suppress the rebellion, four more slave states seceded.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The crisis in Kansas Territory and the neighboring slave state of Missouri turned bloody during what was known as the Bleeding Kansas crisis of the 1850s.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Proslavery *border ruffians* and *Bushwhackers* fought antislavery "free-staters" and *Jayhawkers*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Paramilitary guerrilla warfare became widespread in the area, as a prelude to the Civil War.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The violence would spread to many other places, including the Senate Chamber of the U.S.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Capitol where a Southern Democrat attacked a Northern Republican with a cane as his political allies watched.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Explorer, army veteran, and abolitionist John C.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Frémont ran as the first Republican nominee for president in 1856.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The new party crusaded on the slogan: "Free soil, free silver, free men, Frémont and victory!" Although he lost, the party showed a strong base.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It dominated in Yankee areas of New England, New York and the northern Midwest, and had a strong presence in the rest of the North.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It had almost no support in the South, where it was roundly denounced in 1856–60 as a divisive force that threatened civil war.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The newly-formed Republican Party gained quite a standing in the 1856 to 1857 election cycle in the U.S.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] House and Senate, cementing its status as the primary party for abolitionists and northerners for some time.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Without using the term "containment", the new Party in the mid-1850s proposed a system of containing slavery once it gained control of the national government.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Militant abolitionists demanded *immediate* emancipation, not a slow-acting containment.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some rejected the new party, and in turn its leaders reassured voters they were not trying to abolish slavery in the U.S. altogether, which was politically impossible, and were just working against its spread.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown has been called "the most controversial of all 19th-century Americans".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Whereas Garrison was a pacifist, Brown believed violence was unfortunately necessary to end slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The raid, though unsuccessful in the short term, may have helped Lincoln get elected and moved the Southern states to secede, leading to the Civil War.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians regard Brown as a crazed lunatic, while David S.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Reynolds hails him as the man who "killed slavery, sparked the civil war, and seeded civil rights".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His raid in October 1859 involved a band of 22 men who seized the Federal armory at Harper's Ferry, Virginia (since 1863, West Virginia), knowing it contained tens of thousands of weapons.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown believed the South was on the verge of a gigantic slave uprising and that one spark would set it off.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown's supporters George Luther Stearns, Franklin B.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Sanborn, Thomas Wentworth Higginson, Theodore Parker, Samuel Gridley Howe, and Gerrit Smith were all abolitionists, members of the so-called Secret Six who provided financial backing for Brown's raid.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown's raid, says historian David Potter, "was meant to be of vast magnitude and to produce a revolutionary slave uprising throughout the South".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown hoped to have quickly a small army of runaway slaves, but made no provision to inform these potential runaways, although he got a little local support.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Army was dispatched to put down the raid, and Brown was quickly captured.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] He was tried for treason against the Commonwealth of Virginia, murder, and inciting a slave revolt, was found guilty of all charges, and was hanged.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At his trial, Brown exuded a remarkable zeal and single-mindedness that played directly to Southerners' worst fears.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Under Virginia law there was a month between the sentencing and the hanging, and in those weeks Brown spoke gladly with reporters and anyone else who wanted to see him, and wrote many letters.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Few individuals did more to cause secession than John Brown, because Southerners believed he was right about an impending slave revolt.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The day of his execution, Brown prophesied, "the crimes of this guilty land will never be purged away but with blood.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Civil War began with the stated goal of preserving the Union, and Lincoln said repeatedly that on the topic of slavery, he was only opposed to its spread to the Western territories.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This view of the war progressively changed, one step at a time, as public sentiment evolved, until by 1865 the war was seen in the North as primarily concerned with ending slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first federal act taken against slavery during the war occurred on 16 April 1862, when Lincoln signed the District of Columbia Compensated Emancipation Act, which abolished slavery in Washington, D.C.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A few months later, on June 19, Congress banned slavery in all federal territories, fulfilling Lincoln's 1860 campaign promise.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Meanwhile, the Union suddenly found itself dealing with a steady stream of thousands of escaped slaves, achieving freedom, or so they hoped, by crossing Union lines.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In response, Congress passed the Confiscation Acts, which essentially declared escaped slaves from the South to be confiscated war property, and thus did not have to be returned to their Confederate owners.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, effective 1 January 1863, which declared only those slaves in Confederate states to be free.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Colored Troops began operations in 1863.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fugitive Slave Act of 1850 was repealed in June 1864.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Eventually support for abolition was enough to pass the Thirteenth Amendment, ratified in December 1865, which abolished slavery everywhere in the United States, freeing more than 50,000 people still enslaved in Kentucky and Delaware, in 1865 the only states in which slavery still existed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Thirteenth Amendment also abolished slavery among the Native American tribes.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The abolitionist movement began about the time of the United States' independence.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first abolition organization was the Pennsylvania Abolition Society, which first met in 1775; Benjamin Franklin was its president.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The New York Manumission Society was founded in 1785 by powerful politicians: John Jay, Alexander Hamilton, and Aaron Burr.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] There is quite a bit of confusion about when slavery was abolished in the Northern states, because "abolishing slavery" meant different things in different states.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] These included the first abolition laws in the entire New World: the Massachusetts Constitution, adopted in 1780, declared all men to have rights, making slavery unenforceable, and it disappeared through the individual actions of both masters and slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, what the abolition forces passed in 1799 in New York State was an Act for the *gradual* abolition of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slavery in New York did not officially end until 1827, and more than 70 enslaved people in New York appeared on the 1830 decennial census.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] No slaves appeared in the state's 1840 census.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] New Jersey abolished slavery in 1804, but in 1860 a dozen black people were still held as "perpetual apprentices".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Northwest Ordinance of 1787, the Congress of the Confederation prohibited slavery in the territories northwest of the Ohio River.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At the Constitutional Convention of 1787, slavery was the most contentious topic.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Outright prohibition of slavery was impossible, because the Southern states (Georgia, South Carolina, North Carolina, Virginia, Maryland, and Delaware) would never have agreed to it.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The only restriction on slavery that was agreed to was to allow Congress to prohibit the importation of slaves, and even that was postponed for 20 years.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By that time, all the states except South Carolina had laws abolishing or severely limiting the importation of slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] As he put it, this would "withdraw the citizens of the United States from all further participation in those violations of human rights...which the morality, the reputation, and the best of our country have long been eager to proscribe".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, about 1,000 slaves per year continued to be illegally brought (smuggled) into the United States; see Wanderer and Clotilda.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was primarily via Spanish Florida and the Gulf Coast; the United States acquired Florida from Spain in 1819, effective 1821, in part as a slave-control measure: no imports coming in, and certainly no fugitives escaping into a refuge.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress declined to pass any restriction on the lucrative interstate slave trade, which expanded to replace the supply of African slaves (see Slavery in the United States#Slave trade).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] After 1776, Quaker and Moravian advocates helped persuade numerous slaveholders in the Upper South to free their slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Manumissions increased for nearly two decades.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many individual acts by slaveholders freed thousands of slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slaveholders freed slaves in such numbers that the percentage of free black people in the Upper South increased from 1 to 10 percent, with most of that increase in Virginia, Maryland and Delaware.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1810 three-quarters of blacks in Delaware were free.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The most notable of men offering freedom was Robert Carter III of Virginia, who freed more than 450 people by "Deed of Gift", filed in 1791.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This number was more slaves than any single American had freed before or after.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Often slaveholders came to their decisions by their own struggles in the Revolution; their wills and deeds frequently cited language about the equality of men supporting the decision to set slaves free.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The era's changing economy also encouraged slaveholders to release slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Planters were shifting from labor-intensive tobacco to mixed-crop cultivation and needed fewer slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1860, 91.7% of the blacks in Delaware and 49.7% of those in Maryland were free.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Such early free families often formed the core of artisans, professionals, preachers, and teachers in future generations.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, this did not signal racial equality.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Though free from slavery, blacks still faced immense discrimination.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] For example, Delaware affirmed and reaffirmed black disenfranchisement several times throughout the late 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Delaware's General Assembly enacted harsh black codes throughout the 19th century that restricted travel, property ownership, expression, and socialization for African Americans.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The amendment failed and Missouri became a slave state.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to historian David Brion Davis, this may have been the first time in the world that a political leader openly attacked slavery's perceived legality in such a radical manner.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Postmaster General refused to allow the mails to carry abolition pamphlets to the South.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Northern teachers suspected of abolitionism were expelled from the South, and abolitionist literature was banned.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] One Northerner, Amos Dresser (1812–1904), in 1835 was tried in Nashville, Tennessee, for possessing anti-slavery publications, convicted, and as punishment was whipped publicly.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Southerners rejected the denials of Republicans that they were abolitionists.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They pointed to John Brown's attempt in 1859 to start a slave uprising as proof that multiple Northern conspiracies were afoot to ignite slave rebellions.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Although some abolitionists did call for slave revolts, no evidence of any other Brown-like conspiracy has been discovered.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The North felt threatened as well, for as Eric Foner concludes, "northerners came to view slavery as the very antithesis of the good society, as well as a threat to their own fundamental values and interests".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The famous, "fiery" abolitionist Abby Kelley Foster, from Massachusetts, was considered an "ultra" abolitionist who believed in full civil rights for all black people.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] She held to the view that the freed slaves would colonize Liberia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Parts of the anti-slavery movement became known as "Abby Kellyism".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] She recruited Susan B Anthony and Lucy Stone to the movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Effingham Capron, a cotton and textile scion, who attended the Quaker meeting where Abby Kelley Foster and her family were members, became a prominent abolitionist at the local, state, and national levels.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The local anti-slavery society at Uxbridge, Massachusetts, had more than 25% of the town's population as members.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] McPherson in 1964 defined an abolitionist "as one who before the Civil War had agitated for the immediate, unconditional and total abolition of slavery in the United States".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He notes that many historians have used a broader definition without his emphasis on immediacy.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Thus he does not include opponents of slavery such as Abraham Lincoln or the Republican Party; they called for the immediate end to expansion of slavery before 1861.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As such, abolitionism in the United States was identified by historians as an expression of moralism, it often operated in tandem with another social reform effort, the temperance movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slavery was also attacked, to a lesser degree, as harmful on economic grounds.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Evidence was that the South, with many enslaved African Americans on plantations, was definitely poorer than the North, which had few.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Historians and scholars have largely overlooked the work of black abolitionists; instead, they have focused on only a few black abolitionists, such as Frederick Douglass.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Yet lesser-known black abolitionists, such as Martin Delany and James Monroe Whitfield, also played an undeniably large role in shaping the movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionists had the distinct problem of having to confront an often-hostile American public, while still acknowledging their nationality and struggle.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As a result, many black abolitionists "intentionally adopted aspects of British, New England, and Midwestern cultures".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Furthermore, much of abolitionist rhetoric, and black abolitionist rhetoric in particular, were influenced by the Puritan preaching heritage.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Frederick Douglass was a notable black abolitionist, who significantly contributed to the transnational abolitionist movement through his lecture tours of the United Kingdom from 1845 to 1847.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In particular, he had a connection with Daniel O'Connell: Both O'Connell and Douglass strongly opposed slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] On 4 October 1845, the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society gave Douglass a Bible bound in gold.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] African Americans, with Douglass being a key example, were involving themselves in US foreign relations and influencing British anti-slavery rhetoric.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass was best known for his speeches, and he completed 280 lectures across the UK and Ireland in the 19 months that he was there.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric discussed relationships between power, race, and the popular imagination, showing the complexities of the morality and representation of the abolitionist debate.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass and other black nationalists capitalised on pre-existing political and ideological debates among the UK to reassert the need for abolitionism.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In general, Black female abolitionists had separate motives and rhetorical strategies than White female abolitionists.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were often middle class and members of literary societies; the ones to which they belonged were often made up of solely Black women.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In their activist efforts, they held themselves to high moral standards to be viewed as legitimate by others.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sarah Mapps Douglass, a free-born Quaker who wrote articles for *The Liberator* on abolition also served as the secretary for a literary society for women in Philadelphia, where she emphasized the importance of education and morality for Black women.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women that escaped slavery would sometimes write and publish their slave narratives as a way to argue for abolition.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In opposition to male slave narratives, like Frederick Douglass's, which highlighted literacy, Black women emphasized the communities and relationships they formed as keys to their humanity and right to freedom.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were also keen to highlight their relationship to motherhood, so as to emphasize their shared traits with white women and the ways in which they too could meet traditional expectations of white women.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Harriet Jacobs's *Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl* showcases her grandmother as the matriarch of her family, which shows how enslaved mothers are capable of nurturing like valued white women.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women also played their role in the abolitionist movement, both domestically and internationally, showing involvement in US Foreign Relations.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One notable example was Harriet Jacobs, who produced letters in England reflecting on her experiences as a slave in the US to challenge the pro-slavery movement in the USA.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The London Emancipation Committee published her letters into a book, titled: The Deeper Wrong: Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl, Written by Herself.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The book was not just noticed in reform journals, but in the mainstream press.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lengthy British reviews show how the book helped abolitionists win public support in Britain.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric could be done in literary form, a way for black women to have influence in an international abolitionist movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric was not only a transatlantic movement between Britain and the US, it also had influence in the Caribbean and South America.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The 1833 legal case Mundrucu v Barker also carried international importance in the abolitionist campaign.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In taking a stand against segregation, a black Brazilian immigrant had focused worldwide attention on racism in slaveholding US society.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Here there was division between white Philadelphians who saw black Saint Dominguan refugees as a threat to the city and country's racial order, their way of trying to justify slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This shows the connection between attitudes towards segregation and slavery helped shape black abolitionist rhetoric.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This led to domestic organisations being established by interracial communities, such as the Boston Female Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Working as Jamaican-based writers for New York newspapers between 1840 and 1851, the two black US-Jamaican brothers, Henry and George Davison provided inter-American perspectives on abolitionism.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Henry wrote letters to the National Anti-Slavery Standard.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black Americans had opportunities to write for newspapers, providing publicity and discussion of abolitionist rhetoric.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slavery was moving beyond internal US divisions, but reaching influence outside of the USA.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric was not simply an African-American activity, but involved South American and Caribbean individuals too, showing an international movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Angelina and Sarah Grimké were the first female anti-slavery agents, and played a variety of roles in the abolitionist movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though born in the South, the Grimké sisters became disillusioned with slavery and moved North to get away from it.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Perhaps because of their birthplace, the Grimké sisters' critiques carried particular weight and specificity.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Angelina Grimké spoke of her thrill at seeing white men do manual labor of any kind.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Their perspectives as native Southerners as well as women, brought a new important point of view to the abolitionist movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1836, they moved to New York and began work for the Anti-Slavery Society, where they met and were impressed by William Lloyd Garrison.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The sisters wrote many pamphlets (Angelina's "Appeal to the Christian Women of the South" was the only appeal directly to Southern women to defy slavery laws) and played leadership roles at the first Anti-Slavery Convention of American Women in 1837.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Grimkés later made a notable speaking tour around the north, which culminated in Angelina's February 1838 address to a Committee of the Legislature of Massachusetts.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lucretia Mott was also active in the abolitionist movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though well known for her women's suffrage advocacy, Mott also played an important role in the abolitionist movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] During four decades, she delivered sermons about abolitionism, women's rights, and a host of other issues.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Mott acknowledged her Quaker beliefs' determinative role in affecting her abolitionist sentiment.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley Foster, with a strong Quaker heritage, helped lead Susan B.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony and Lucy Stone into the abolition movement, and encouraged them to take on a role in political activism.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] the first National Women's Rights Convention, held in Worcester, Massachusetts, in 1850.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (The better-known Seneca Falls Convention, held in 1848, was not national).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She was an "ultra" abolitionist who believed in immediate and complete civil rights for all slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 1841, however, she had resigned from the Quakers over disputes about not allowing anti-slavery speakers in meeting houses (including the Uxbridge monthly meeting where she had attended with her family), and the group disowned her.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley became a leading speaker and the leading fundraiser for the American Anti-slavery Society.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Radical abolitionism became known as "Abby Kelleyism".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Other leaders in the abolitionist movement were Lydia Maria Child, Elizabeth Cady Stanton, Susan B.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony, Harriet Tubman, and Sojourner Truth.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But even beyond these well-known women, abolitionism maintained impressive support from white middle-class and some black women.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was these women who performed many of the logistical, day-to-day tasks that made the movement successful.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They raised money, wrote and distributed propaganda pieces, drafted and signed petitions, and lobbied the legislatures.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though abolitionism sowed the seeds of the women's rights movement, most women became involved in abolitionism because of a gendered religious worldview, and the idea that they had feminine, moral responsibilities.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, in the winter of 1831–1832, women sent three petitions to the Virginia legislature, advocating emancipation of the state's slave population.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The only precedent for such action was Catharine Beecher's organization of a petition protesting the Cherokee removal.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Virginia petitions, while the first of their kind, were by no means the last.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Similar backing increased leading up to the Civil War.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even as women played crucial roles in abolitionism, the movement simultaneously helped stimulate women's-rights efforts.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A full 10 years before the Seneca Falls Convention, the Grimké sisters were travelling and lecturing about their experiences with slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As Gerda Lerner says, the Grimkés understood their actions' great impact.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "In working for the liberation of the slave," Lerner writes, "Sarah and Angelina Grimké found the key to their own liberation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] And the consciousness of the significance of their actions was clearly before them.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Women gained important experiences in public speaking and organizing that stood them in good stead going forward.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Grimké sisters' public speaking played a critical part in legitimizing women's place in the public sphere.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Some Christian women created cent societies to benefit abolition movements, where many women in a church would each pledge to donate one cent a week to help abolitionist causes.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even though women were not allowed full access to political and religious spaces, they still played a big role in the abolitionist movement through both public activism and behind-the-scenes activism.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As historian Julie Roy Jeffrey explains, a lot of women relied on their religious faith and authority to speak out against slavery and challenge male-led church systems that tried to keep them quiet.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They believed slavery went against Christian values and saw it as a deep moral wrong.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In their speeches and writing, they made it clear that true faith could not exist alongside a system that discriminated against people.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Women like Sarah Otis Ernst and Maria Child used persuasive writing, public speeches, and organizing work to fight not just slavery, but also the powerful systems that kept it going.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Ernst was a strong Garrisonian who got frustrated when mainstream abolitionists started watering down their message.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She did not like that people in the movement were trying to be more politically strategic instead of sticking to the original beliefs, like full racial equality, immediate emancipation, and refusing to work with pro-slavery systems.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] At the 1852 American and Foreign Antislavery Society convention, around two-thirds of the 2,000 people there were women.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] That says a lot about how involved women were, even though they often got written out of the story.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They could not vote, but they used writing, speeches, and journalism to influence politics and public opinion.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Their activism was real, public, and tied directly into national conversations.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But not all women approached the movement the same way.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There were clear differences between how white and Black women operated, and sometimes those differences caused conflict.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] White women, especially ones who were more religious, focused a lot on the moral and spiritual arguments.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They used Christian values to call out slavery as a sin and tried to appeal to other white Americans by framing it as a moral crisis.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, Lydia Maria Child wrote about Christian duty and compassion to get people on board.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But that type of activism did not always connect with what Black women were facing every day.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] And even inside the abolitionist circles, Black women were still often pushed to the side.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were not always given speaking time, leadership roles, or space in published work.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sojourner Truth had to fight just to speak at some events, and even then, people questioned her.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] White women could usually speak and be heard if they used moral language.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women had to work twice as hard just to get into the room.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They faced racism from inside the movement and also from the outside world, which made it even harder for their voices to be heard.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Richmond talks about how central Black women were to abolition, even though they have been left out of most of the history.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Women like Sojourner Truth, Maria Stewart, and Harriet Tubman struggled not only for the abolition of slavery but for gender and racial equality as well".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were not just giving speeches, they were founding antislavery groups, organizing communities, and building transatlantic networks.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were working through both racism and sexism and still finding ways to be powerful voices.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Truth's line "Ain’t I a Woman?" and Stewart saying she had to "stand for justice wherever I find it" show how they were calling out not just slavery, but the whole system that tried to silence them.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Harriet Tubman took a different route; she led people to freedom through the Underground Railroad and even worked for the Union Army.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women's abolitionism looked different from that of white women.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was rooted in their personal experience and often more direct and action-focused.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They made sure the fight for abolition was not just about ending slavery, but also about achieving full equality and justice.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The July 1848 Seneca Falls Convention grew out of a partnership between Lucretia Mott and Elizabeth Cady Stanton that blossomed while the two worked, at first, on abolitionist issues.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Indeed, the two met at the World's Anti-Slavery Convention in the summer of 1840.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Mott brought oratorical skills and an impressive reputation as an abolitionist to the nascent women's rights movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionism brought together active women and enabled them to make political and personal connections while honing communication and organizational skills.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even Sojourner Truth, commonly associated with abolitionism, delivered her first documented public speech at the 1850 National Women's Rights Convention in Worcester.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There, she argued for women's reform activism.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The religious component of American abolitionism was great.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It began with the Quakers, then moved to the other Protestants with the Second Great Awakening of the early 19th century.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Saying slavery was sinful made its evil easy to understand, and tended to arouse fervor for the cause.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The debate about slavery was often based on what the Bible said or did not say about it.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] John Brown, who had studied the Bible for the ministry, proclaimed that he was "an instrument of God".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Second Great Awakening of the 1820s and 1830s in religion inspired groups that undertook many types of social reform.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For some that included the immediate abolition of slavery as they considered it sinful to hold slaves as well as to tolerate slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Opposition to slavery, for example, was one of the works of piety of the Methodist Churches, which were established by John Wesley.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Abolitionist" had several meanings at the time.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The followers of William Lloyd Garrison, including Wendell Phillips and Frederick Douglass, demanded the "immediate abolition of slavery", hence the name, also called "immediatism".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A more pragmatic group of abolitionists, such as Theodore Weld and Arthur Tappan, wanted immediate action, but were willing to support a program of gradual emancipation, with a long intermediate stage.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The *True Wesleyan* a periodical founded by Orange Scott and Jotham Horton was used to disseminate abolitionist views.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Methodist and Quaker branches of Christianity played an integral part in the formulation of abolitionist ideology in the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Anti-slavery men", such as John Quincy Adams, did not call slavery a sin.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They called it an evil feature of society as a whole.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They did what they could to limit slavery and end it where possible, but were not part of any abolitionist group.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, in 1841, John Quincy Adams represented the *Amistad* African slaves in the Supreme Court of the United States and argued that they should be set free.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the last years before the war, "anti-slavery" could refer to the Northern majority, such as Abraham Lincoln, who opposed expansion of slavery or its influence, as by the Kansas–Nebraska Act or the Fugitive Slave Act.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many Southerners called all these abolitionists, without distinguishing them from the Garrisonians.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish Catholics in the United States seldom challenged the role of slavery in society as it was protected at that time by the U.S.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They viewed the abolitionists as anti-Catholic and anti-Irish.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish Catholics were generally well received by Democrats in the South.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, most Irish Nationalists and Fenians supported the abolition of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Daniel O'Connell, the Catholic leader of the Irish in Ireland, supported abolition in the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He organized a petition in Ireland with 60,000 signatures urging the Irish of the United States to support abolition.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] John O'Mahony, a founder of the Irish Republican Brotherhood was an abolitionist and served as colonel in the 69th Infantry Regiment during the Civil War.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Irish Catholics in the United States were recent immigrants; most were poor and very few owned slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They had to compete with free blacks for unskilled labor jobs.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They saw abolitionism as the militant wing of evangelical anti-Catholic Protestantism.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Catholic Church in the United States had long ties in slaveholding Maryland and Louisiana.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1861, the Archbishop of New York wrote to Secretary of War Cameron: "That the Church is opposed to slavery ...
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Her doctrine on that subject is, that it is a crime to reduce men naturally free to a condition of servitude and bondage, as slaves." No American bishop supported extra-political abolition or interference with states' rights before the Civil War.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The secular Germans of the Forty-Eighter immigration were largely anti-slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Prominent Forty-Eighters included Carl Schurz and Friedrich Hecker.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] German Lutherans seldom took a position on slavery, but German Methodists were anti-slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Both Garrison's newspaper *The Liberator* and his book *Thoughts on African Colonization* (1832) arrived shortly after publication at Western Reserve College, in Hudson, Ohio, which was briefly the center of abolitionist discourse in the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (John Brown grew up in Hudson.) The readers, including college president Charles Backus Storrs, found Garrison's arguments and evidence convincing.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolition versus colonization rapidly became the primary issue on the campus, to the point that Storrs complained in writing that nothing else was being discussed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The college's chaplain and theology professor Beriah Green said that "his *Thoughts* and his paper (*The Liberator*) are worthy of the eye and the heart of every American." Green delivered in the college chapel in November and December 1832 four sermons supporting immediate abolition of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These so offended the college's trustees, more conservative than either the students or the faculty, that Green resigned, expecting that he would be fired.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Elizur Wright, another professor, resigned soon afterwards and became the first secretary of the American Anti-Slavery Society, of which Green was the first president.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Storrs contracted tuberculosis, took a leave of absence, and died within six months.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This left the school with only one of its four professors.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Green was soon hired as the new president of the Oneida Institute.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under the previous president, George Washington Gale, there had been a mass walkout of students; among the issues was Gale's lack of support for abolition.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He accepted the position on conditions that 1) he be allowed to preach "immediatism", immediate emancipation, and 2) that African-American students be admitted on the same terms as white students.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These were accepted, and we know the names of 16 Blacks who studied there.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Native American students, of whom we know the names of two, were openly accepted as well.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under Green, Oneida became "a hotbed of anti-slavery activity." It was "abolitionist to the core, more so than any other American college." For Presbyterian minister and Bible professor Green, slavery was not just an evil but a sin, and abolitionism was what Christ's principles mandated.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under him a cadre of abolitionists was trained, who then carried the abolitionist message, via lectures and sermons, throughout the North.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many future well-known black leaders and abolitionists were students at Oneida while Green was president.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These include William Forten (son of James Forten), Alexander Crummell, Rev.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Oneida Institute did not have an incident, like that of Western Reserve, which brought national attention to it.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Its successor, Lane Seminary, in Cincinnati, did.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Lane was Oneida moved west." Leading the exodus from Oneida was a former Oneida student, and private student of Gale before that, Theodore Dwight Weld.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He greatly impressed the philanthropist brothers and abolitionists Arthur and Lewis Tappan.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They hired him to report on the movement nationally, and specifically to find a new location for their funding, since Oneida, a manual labor school, was a disappointment, according to Weld and his student followers.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] At the same time that Weld was scouting a location for a new school, the barely-functioning Lane Seminary was looking for students.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Based on Weld's recommendation, the Tappans started giving Lane the financial support they had previously given Oneida.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Weld, though on paper enrolled as a student at Lane, was de facto its head, choosing, through his recommendations to the Tappans, the president (Lyman Beecher, after Charles Grandison Finney, who became later the second president of Oberlin, turned it down), and telling the trustees whom to hire.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The group of students led by Weld constituted the first student movement in the history of the country.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He chose Lane, and they followed him there.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] When he soon left Lane for another new, struggling institution, Oberlin, they did so too, as a group.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Students, many of whom considered him the real leader of Lane, responded to Weld's announcement of the new school in Cincinnati.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lane ended up with about 100 students, the most of any seminary in America.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One of Weld's key contentions (and of Puritan abolition sentiment in general) was that slavery was inherently anti-family.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] While slave marriage was illegal, it happened frequently.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners expected their slaves to have many children to replace their numbers; Virginia and Maryland "exported" slaves to the Deep South—they were an asset like cattle—after Congress had banned the importation of slaves in 1808.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Since slaves were property they were frequently bought and sold, ripping apart families.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In his 1839 book *American Slavery as It Is*, Weld showed just how brutal the slave trade was towards families.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] To the very family-focused Puritans, this was one of the greatest crimes of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Weld's descriptions of families destroyed would later serve as the basis for scenes in *Uncle Tom's Cabin*, including Uncle Tom's being sold and separated from the children.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] No sooner had this disparate group of former Oneida students and others arrived at Lane, under the leadership of Weld, than they formed an anti-slavery society.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They then proceeded to hold a well-publicized series of debates on abolition versus African colonization, lasting 18 evenings, and decided that abolition was a much better solution to slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In fact no real debate took place, since no one appeared to defend colonization.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These "debates", which were well publicized, alarmed Lane's president Lyman Beecher and the school's trustees.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Adding to their alarm were the classes the students were holding in the Black community, teaching Blacks to read.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Fearing violence, since Cincinnati was strongly anti-abolitionist (see Cincinnati riots of 1829), they immediately prohibited any future such "off-the-topic" discussions and activities.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The students, again led by Weld, felt that abolitionism was so important – it was their responsibility as Christians to promote it – and they resigned *en masse*, joined by Asa Mahan, a trustee who supported the students.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] With support from the Tappans, they briefly tried to establish a new seminary, but as this did not prove a practical solution they accepted a proposal that they move as a group to the new Oberlin Collegiate Institute.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Due to its students' anti-slavery position, Oberlin soon became one of the most liberal colleges and accepted African-American students.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Along with Garrison, Northcutt and Collins were proponents of immediate abolition.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley Foster became an "ultra abolitionist" and a follower of William Lloyd Garrison.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony as well as Elizabeth Cady Stanton into the anti-slavery cause.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] After 1840, "abolition" usually referred to positions similar to Garrison's.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was largely an ideological movement led by about 3,000 people, including free blacks and free people of color, many of whom, such as Frederick Douglass in Rochester, New York, and Robert Purvis and James Forten in Philadelphia, played prominent leadership roles.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass became legally free during a two-year stay in England, as British supporters raised funds to purchase his freedom from his American owner Thomas Auld, and also helped fund his abolitionist newspapers in the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionism had a strong religious base including Quakers, and people converted by the revivalist fervor of the Second Great Awakening, led by Charles Finney in the North, in the 1830s.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Belief in abolition contributed to the formation of Christian denominations, such as the Free Methodist Church.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Evangelical abolitionists founded some colleges, most notably Bates College in Maine and Oberlin College in Ohio.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The movement attracted such figures as Yale president Noah Porter and Harvard president Thomas Hill.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the mid nineteenth century, American abolitionism was shaped by British ideological and organisational influences.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A key part of this exchange was the intersection of abolitionism and free trade ideology.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] British reformers such as Richard Cobden and the Anti Corn Law League inspired American abolitionists to promote free trade arguing that it was morally and economically aligned to abolition in the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Leaders like Joshua Leavitt, campaigner for the Liberty Party, argued that repealing British tariffs would reduce US reliance on Southern slave grown cotton and open markets to free labour goods from the North.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Another prominent British activist was George Thompson, who toured the US several times where he delivered speeches connecting Free Trade to the American abolition cause.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Figures like Cobden and Thompson were a direct influence on the ideology of Lloyd Garrison.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Another movement called the Free-produce movement extended across the Atlantic.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This movement aimed to boycott goods produced by enslaved Africans.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The movement was connected to British activist Joseph Sturge and the idea that a free market allowed for consumer morality.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sociologist Cecilia Walsh-Russo developed the term 'mutual brokerage' to refer to the interchange of ideas within UK-US abolitionist movements.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She refers to the interactions which allowed ideas and political strategy to co-develop, rather than suggesting one learned from the other.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Walsh-Russo cites the 1840 World Anti-Slavery Convention in London as an example of mutual brokerage.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She claims the exclusion of women as delegates, despite their presence at the events forced transatlantic abolitionist to re-assess their understanding of political participation and democracy, often leading to more progressive views in UK and US activism.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Despite exclusion from the conference women asserted their right to participate in the abolitionist cause by using informal setting such as salons to promote abolition.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] William Lloyd Garrison also engaged in Irish politics.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He communicated with key figures like Daniel O'Connell, which shaped his understanding of abolition as 'universal emancipation'.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrisonian abolitionists also used Ireland and the Irish as tools of comparison especially in combatting the American Colonization Society.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] However, efforts to forge direct relations between Irish Americans and African Americans largely failed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The 1842 Address from the People of Ireland to Their Countrymen and Countrywomen in America, written by Irish abolitionists and signed by O'Connell, urged Irish Americans to support abolition and racial equality.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrisonians hoped this would foster diasporic responsibility among the Irish but it was rejected by most.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish immigrants, perhaps due to a desire to assimilate in the US, were overall not supportive of the abolitionist cause.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It is easy to overstate the support for abolitionism in the North.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A majority of white Southerners, though by no means all, supported slavery; there was a growing feeling in favor of emancipation in North Carolina, Maryland, Virginia, and Kentucky, until the panic resulting from Nat Turner's 1831 revolt put an end to it.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But only a minority in the North supported abolition, seen as an extreme, "radical" measure.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (See Radical Republicans.) Horace Greeley remarked in 1854 that he had "never been able to discover any strong, pervading, over-ruling Anti Slavery sentiment in the Free States." Free blacks were subject in the North as well as in the South to conditions almost inconceivable today (2019).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Although the picture is neither uniform nor static, in general free blacks in the North were not citizens and could neither vote nor hold public office.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They could not give testimony in court and their word was never taken against a white man's word, as a result of which white crimes against blacks were rarely punished.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black children could not study in the public schools, even though Black taxpayers helped support them, and there were only a handful of schools for Black students, like the African Free School in New York, the Abiel Smith School in Boston, and the Watkins Academy for Negro Youth in Baltimore.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] When schools for negroes were set up in Ohio in the 1830s, the teacher of one slept in it every night "for fear whites would burn it", and at another, "a vigilance committee threatened to tar and feather [the teacher] and ride her on a rail if she did not leave".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (Oberlin Collegiate Institute was the first college that survived to admit them by policy; the Oneida Institute was a short-lived predecessor.) In wages, housing, access to services, and transportation, separate but equal or Jim Crow treatment would have been a great improvement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The proposal to create the country's first college for negros, in New Haven, Connecticut, got such strong local opposition (New Haven Excitement) that it was quickly abandoned.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Schools in which blacks and whites studied together in Canaan, New Hampshire, and Canterbury, Connecticut, were physically destroyed by mobs.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (The prosecutor was Francis Scott Key.) In Savannah, Georgia, the mayor and alderman protected an abolitionist visitor from a mob.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the North there was far more serious violence by mobs, what the press sometimes called "mobocracy".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lovejoy, who published an abolitionist newspaper, was killed by a mob in Illinois.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Only six months later, the large, modern, and expensive new hall which the Pennsylvania Anti-Slavery Society built in Philadelphia in 1838, was burned by a mob three days after it opened.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There were other anti-abolitionist riots in New York (1834), Cincinnati (1829, 1836, and 1841), Norwich, Connecticut (1834), Washington, D.C.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (1835), Philadelphia (1842), and Granville, Ohio (following the Ohio State Anti-Slavery Convention, 1836), although there was also a pro-abolition riot (more precisely a pro-fugitive slave riot) in Boston in 1836 (and see Jerry Rescue).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Between 1835 and 1838, anti-abolitionist violence "settled into a routine feature of public life in virtually all the major northern cities".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Giving to blacks the same rights that whites had, as Garrison called for, was "far outside the mainstream of opinion in the 1830s." Some opposed even allowing blacks to join abolitionist organizations.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionists nationwide were outraged by the murder of white abolitionist and journalist Elijah Parish Lovejoy by a proslavery mob in Alton, Illinois on 7 November 1837.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Six months later, Pennsylvania Hall, an abolitionist venue in Philadelphia, was burnt to the ground by another proslavery mob on May 17, 1838.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Both events contributed to the growing American debate over slavery and marked an increase in violence against abolitionists in the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Amos Dresser, a participant in the Lane Debates, was publicly whipped in Nashville.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A gallows with a note from "Judge Lynch" was erected in front of Garrison's office.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He, along with the Tappans, was hung in effigy in Charleston, S.C.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Southern post offices burned rather than delivered abolitionist publications, in which they were supported by the national Post Office.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners were angry over the attacks on what some Southerners (including the politician John C.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Calhoun) referred to as their "peculiar institution" of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Starting in the 1830s, Southerners developed a vehement and growing ideological defense of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners claimed that slavery was not a necessary evil, or an evil of any sort; slavery was a positive good for masters and slaves alike, and it was explicitly sanctioned by God.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Biblical arguments were made in defense of slavery by religious leaders such as the Rev.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Ross and political leaders such as Jefferson Davis.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Southern Biblical interpretations contradicted those of the abolitionists; a popular one was that the curse on Noah's son Ham and his descendants in Africa justified enslaving blacks.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionists responded, denying that either God or the Bible endorses slavery, at least as practiced in the Antebellum South.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the early 19th century, a variety of organizations were established that advocated relocation of black people from the United States, most prominently the American Colonization Society (ACS), founded in 1816.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The ACS enjoyed the support of prominent Southern leaders such as Henry Clay and James Monroe, who saw it as a convenient means of relocating free blacks, whom they perceived as a threat to their control over enslaved blacks.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Starting in the 1820s, the ACS and affiliated state societies assisted a few thousand free blacks to move to the newly established colonies in West Africa that were to form the Republic of Liberia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] From 1832 onward most of the migrants were enslaved people who had been freed on the condition that they go to Liberia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many migrants died of local diseases, but enough survived for Liberia to declare independence in 1847.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Americo-Liberians formed a ruling elite whose treatment of the native population followed the lines of disdain for African culture they had acquired in America.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Most African Americans opposed colonization, and simply wanted to be given the rights of free citizens in the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One notable opponent of such plans was the wealthy free black abolitionist James Forten of Philadelphia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1832, prominent white abolitionist William Lloyd Garrison published his book *Thoughts on African Colonization*, in which he attacked severely the policy of sending blacks to (not "back to") Africa, and specifically the American Colonization Society.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Colonization Society, which he had previously supported, is "a creature without heart, without brains, eyeless, unnatural, hypocritical, relentless and unjust." "Colonization", according to Garrison, was not a plan to eliminate slavery, but to protect it.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrison also pointed out that a majority of the colonists died of disease, and the number of free blacks actually resettled in the future Liberia was minute in comparison to the number of slaves in the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The first country to fully outlaw slavery was France in 1315, though it was later used in its colonies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The first country to abolish and punish slavery for indigenous people was Spain with the New Laws in 1542.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Under the actions of Toyotomi Hideyoshi, chattel slavery was abolished across Japan since 1590, though other forms of forced labor were used during World War II.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The first and only country to self-liberate from slavery was a former French colony, Haiti, as a result of the Revolution of 1791–1804.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The British abolitionist movement began in the late 18th century, and the 1772 Somersett case established that slavery did not exist in English law.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1807, the slave trade was made illegal throughout the British Empire, though existing slaves in British colonies were not liberated until the Slavery Abolition Act 1833.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In the United States, Pennsylvania and Vermont were the first states to abolish slavery, Vermont in 1777 and Pennsylvania in 1780 (Vermont did not join the Union until 1791).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] By 1804, the rest of the northern states had abolished slavery, but it remained legal in southern states.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] By 1808, the United States outlawed the importation of slaves and in 1865 outlawed slavery except as a punishment.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In Eastern Europe, groups organized to abolish the enslavement of the Roma in Wallachia and Moldavia between 1843 and 1855, and to emancipate the serfs in Russia in 1861.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The United States would pass the 13th Amendment in December 1865 after having just fought a bloody Civil War, ending slavery "except as a punishment for crime".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1888, Brazil became the last country in the Americas to outlaw slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] As the Empire of Japan annexed Asian countries, from the late 19th century onwards, archaic institutions including slavery were abolished in those countries.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1948, slavery was declared illegal in the United Nations' Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] By this time, the Arab world was the only region in the world where institutional chattel slavery was still legal.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Slavery in Saudi Arabia, slavery in Yemen and slavery in Dubai were abolished in 1962–1963, with slavery in Oman following in 1970.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Mauritania is the latest country to officially abolish slavery, with a presidential decree in 1981.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Today, child and adult slavery and forced labor are illegal in almost all countries, as well as being against international law, but human trafficking for labor and for sexual slavery continues to affect tens of millions of adults and children.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Balthild of Chelles, herself a former slave, queen consort of Neustria and Burgundy by marriage to Clovis II, became regent in 657 since the king, her son Chlothar III, was only five years old.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] At some unknown date during her rule, she abolished the trade of slaves, although not slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Moreover, her (and contemporaneous Saint Eligius') favorite charity was to buy and free slaves, especially children.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Slavery started to dwindle and would be superseded by serfdom.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1315, Louis X, king of France, published a decree proclaiming that "France signifies freedom" and that any slave setting foot on French soil should be freed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] This prompted subsequent governments to circumscribe slavery in the overseas colonies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Some cases of African slaves freed by setting foot on French soil were recorded such as the example of a Norman slave merchant who tried to sell slaves in Bordeaux in 1571.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] He was arrested and his slaves were freed according to a declaration of the Parlement of Guyenne which stated that slavery was intolerable in France, although it is a misconception that there were 'no slaves in France'; thousands of African slaves were present in France during the 18th century.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Born into slavery in Saint Domingue, Thomas-Alexandre Dumas became free when his father brought him to France in 1776.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] As in other New World colonies, the French relied on the Atlantic slave trade for labor for their sugar cane plantations in their Caribbean colonies; the French West Indies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In addition, French colonists in *Louisiane* in North America held slaves, particularly in the South around New Orleans, where they established sugarcane plantations.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Louis XIV's *Code Noir* regulated the slave trade and institution in the colonies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] It included the right to marry, gather publicly or take Sundays off.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Although the *Code Noir* authorized and codified cruel corporal punishment against slaves under certain conditions, it forbade slave owners to torture them or to separate families.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] It also demanded enslaved Africans receive instruction in the Catholic faith, implying that Africans were human beings endowed with a soul, a fact French law did not admit until then.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] It resulted in a far higher percentage of Black people being free in 1830 (13.2% in Louisiana compared to 0.8% in Mississippi).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] They were on average exceptionally literate, with a significant number of them owning businesses, properties, and even slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Other free people of colour, such as Julien Raimond, spoke out against slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The *Code Noir* also forbade interracial marriages, but it was often ignored in French colonial society and the mulattoes became an intermediate caste between whites and blacks, while in the British colonies mulattoes and blacks were considered equal and discriminated against equally.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] During the Age of Enlightenment, many philosophers wrote pamphlets against slavery and its moral and economical justifications, including Montesquieu in *The Spirit of the Laws* (1748) and Denis Diderot in the *Encyclopédie*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1788, Jacques Pierre Brissot founded the Society of the Friends of the Blacks (*Société des Amis des Noirs*) to work for the abolition of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] After the Revolution, on 4 April 1792, France granted free people of colour full citizenship.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The slave revolt, in the largest Caribbean French colony of Saint-Domingue in 1791, was the beginning of what became the Haitian Revolution led by formerly enslaved people like Georges Biassou, Toussaint L'Ouverture, and Jean-Jacques Dessalines.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The rebellion swept through the north of the colony, and with it came freedom to thousands of enslaved blacks, but also violence and death.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1793, French Civil Commissioners in St.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Domingue and abolitionists, Léger-Félicité Sonthonax and Étienne Polverel, issued the first emancipation proclamation of the modern world (Decree of 16 Pluviôse An II).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The Convention sent them to safeguard the allegiance of the population to revolutionary France.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The proclamation resulted in crucial military strategy as it gradually brought most of the black troops into the French fold and kept the colony under the French flag for most of the conflict.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The connection with France lasted until blacks and free people of colour formed L'armée indigène in 1802 to resist Napoleon's Expédition de Saint-Domingue.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Victory over the French in the decisive Battle of Vertières finally led to independence and the creation of present Haiti in 1804.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The convention, the first elected Assembly of the First Republic (1792–1804), on 4 February 1794, under the leadership of Maximilien Robespierre, abolished slavery in law in France and its colonies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Abbé Grégoire and the Society of the Friends of the Blacks were part of the abolitionist movement, which had laid important groundwork in building anti-slavery sentiment in the metropole.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The first article of the law stated that "Slavery was abolished" in the French colonies, while the second article stated that "slave-owners would be indemnified" with financial compensation for the value of their slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The French constitution passed in 1795 included in the declaration of the Rights of Man that slavery was abolished.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] During the French Revolutionary Wars, French slave-owners joined the counter-revolution en masse and, through the Whitehall Accord, they threatened to move the French Caribbean colonies to British control, as Great Britain still allowed slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Fearing secession from these islands, successfully lobbied by planters and concerned about revenues from the West Indies, and influenced by the slaveholder family of his wife, Napoleon Bonaparte decided to re-establish slavery after becoming First Consul.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] He promulgated the law of 20 May 1802 and sent military governors and troops to the colonies to impose it.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] On 10 May 1802, Colonel Delgrès launched a rebellion in Guadeloupe against Napoleon's representative, General Richepanse.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The rebellion was repressed, and slavery was re-established.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The news of the Law of 4 February 1794 that abolished slavery in France and its colonies and the revolution led by Colonel Delgrès sparked another wave of rebellion in Saint-Domingue.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] From 1802 Napoleon sent more than 20,000 troops to the island, two-thirds died, mostly from yellow fever.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Seeing the failure of the Saint-Domingue expedition, in 1803 Napoleon decided to sell the Louisiana Territory to the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The French governments initially refused to recognize Haïti.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] It forced the nation to pay a substantial amount of reparations (which it could ill afford) for losses during the revolution and did not recognize its government until 1825.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] France was a signatory to the first multilateral treaty for the suppression of the slave trade, the Treaty for the Suppression of the African Slave Trade (1841), but the king, Louis Philippe I, declined to ratify it.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] On 27 April 1848, under the Second Republic (1848–1852), the decree-law written by Victor Schœlcher abolished slavery in the remaining colonies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The state bought the slaves from the *colons* (white colonists; *Békés* in Creole), and then freed them.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] At about the same time, France started colonizing Africa and had gained possession of much of West Africa by 1900.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1905, the French abolished slavery in most of French West Africa.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The French also attempted to abolish Tuareg slavery following the Kaocen Revolt.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In the region of the Sahel, slavery has long persisted.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The abolition wasn't strictly put in place.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Several french territories kept practising slavery until 1904 as was the case in Senegal or 1894 in Soudan.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The abolition was not strictly enforced.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Passed on 10 May 2001, the Taubira law officially acknowledges slavery and the Atlantic slave trade as a crime against humanity.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] 10 May was chosen as the day dedicated to recognition of the crime of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] James Oglethorpe was among the first to articulate the Enlightenment case against slavery, banning it in the Province of Georgia on humanitarian grounds, and arguing against it in Parliament.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Soon after Oglethorpe's death in 1785, Sharp and More united with William Wilberforce and others in forming the Clapham Sect.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The Somersett case in 1772, in which a fugitive slave was freed with the judgement that slavery did not exist under English common law, helped launch the British movement to abolish slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Though anti-slavery sentiments were widespread by the late 18th century, many colonies and emerging nations continued to use slave labor: Dutch, French, British, Spanish, and Portuguese territories in the West Indies, South America, and the Southern United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] After the American Revolution established the United States, many Loyalists who fled the Northern United States immigrated to the British province of Quebec, bringing an English majority population as well as many slaves, leading the province to ban the institution in 1793 (see Slavery in Canada).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1787, the Society for Effecting the Abolition of the Slave Trade was formed in London.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The last known form of enforced servitude of adults (villeinage) had disappeared in England by the beginning of the 17th century.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1569 a court considered the case of Cartwright, who had bought a slave from Russia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The court ruled English law could not recognize slavery, as it was never established officially.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] This ruling was overshadowed by later developments; it was upheld in 1700 by the Lord Chief Justice John Holt when he ruled that a slave became free as soon as he arrived in England.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] During the English Civil Wars of the mid-seventeenth century, sectarian radicals challenged slavery and other threats to personal freedom.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Their ideas influenced many antislavery thinkers in the eighteenth century.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In addition to English colonists importing slaves to the North American colonies, by the 18th century, traders began to import slaves from Africa, India and East Asia (where they were trading) to London and Edinburgh to work as personal servants.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Some of the first freedom suits, court cases in the British Isles to challenge the legality of slavery, took place in Scotland in 1755 and 1769.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Each of the slaves had been baptized in Scotland and challenged the legality of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] They set the precedent of legal procedure in British courts that would later lead to successful outcomes for the plaintiffs.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In these cases, deaths of the plaintiff and defendant, respectively, brought an end before court decisions.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] African slaves were not bought or sold in London but were brought by masters from other areas.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Together with people from other nations, especially non-Christian, Africans were considered foreigners, not able to be English subjects.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] At the time, England had no naturalization procedure.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The African slaves' legal status was unclear until 1772 and Somersett's Case, when the fugitive slave James Somersett forced a decision by the courts.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Somersett had escaped, and his master, Charles Steuart, had him captured and imprisoned on board a ship, intending to ship him to Jamaica to be resold into slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] While in London, Somersett had been baptized; three godparents issued a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The case received national attention, and five advocates supported the action on behalf of Somersett.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Although the exact legal implications of the judgement are unclear when analysed by lawyers, the judgement was generally taken at the time to have determined that slavery did not exist under English common law and was thus prohibited in England.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The decision did not apply to the British overseas territories; by then, for example, the American colonies had established slavery by positive laws.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The Court of Session of Scotland ruled against him, saying that chattel slavery was not recognized under the law of Scotland, and slaves could seek court protection to leave a master or avoid being forcibly removed from Scotland to be returned to slavery in the colonies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] But at the same time, legally mandated, hereditary slavery of Scots persons in Scotland had existed from 1606 and continued until 1799, when colliers and salters were emancipated by an act of the Parliament of Great Britain (39 Geo.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Skilled workers, they were restricted to a place and could be sold with the works.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] 28) was intended to end what the act referred to as "a state of slavery and bondage", but that was ineffective, necessitating the 1799 act.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In the 1776 book *The Wealth of Nations*, Adam Smith argued for the abolition of slavery on economic grounds.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Smith pointed out that slavery incurred security, housing, and food costs that the use of free labor would not, and opined that free workers would be more productive because they would have personal economic incentives to work harder.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The death rate (and thus repurchase cost) of slaves was also high, and people are less productive when not allowed to choose the type of work they prefer, are illiterate, and are forced to live and work in miserable and unhealthy conditions.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The free labor markets and international free trade that Smith preferred would also result in different prices and allocations that Smith believed would be more efficient and productive for consumers.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Prior to the American Revolution, there were few significant initiatives in the American colonies that led to the abolitionist movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Benjamin Kent was the lawyer who took on most of the cases of slaves suing their masters for personal illegal enslavement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] He was the first lawyer to successfully establish a slave's freedom.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In addition, Brigadier General Samuel Birch created the *Book of Negroes*, to establish which slaves were free after the war.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1783, an anti-slavery movement began among the British public to end slavery throughout the British Empire.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Thomas Clarkson became the group's most prominent researcher, gathering vast amounts of data on the trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] One aspect of abolitionism during this period was the effective use of images such as the famous Josiah Wedgwood "Am I Not A Man and a Brother?" anti-slavery medallion of 1787.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Clarkson described the medallion as "promoting the cause of justice, humanity and freedom".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The 1792 Slave Trade Bill passed the House of Commons mangled and mutilated by the modifications and amendments of Pitt, it lay for years, in the House of Lords.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Biographer William Hague considers the unfinished abolition of the slave trade to be Pitt's greatest failure.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The Slave Trade Act 1807 was passed by the British Parliament on 25 March 1807, making the slave trade illegal throughout the British Empire.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Britain enforced the abolition of the trade because the act made trading slaves within British territories illegal.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] However, the act repealed the Amelioration Act 1798 which attempted to improve conditions for slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The end of the slave trade did not end slavery as a whole.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In the 1820s, the abolitionist movement revived to campaign against the institution of slavery itself.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1823 the first Anti-Slavery Society, the Society for the Mitigation and Gradual Abolition of Slavery Throughout the British Dominions, was founded.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Many of its members had previously campaigned against the slave trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] On 28 August 1833, the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 was passed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] It purchased the slaves from their masters and paved the way for the abolition of slavery throughout the British Empire by 1838, after which the first Anti-Slavery Society was wound up.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1839, the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society was formed by Joseph Sturge, which attempted to outlaw slavery worldwide and also to pressure the government to help enforce the suppression of the slave trade by declaring slave traders to be pirates.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The world's oldest international human rights organization, it continues today as Anti-Slavery International.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Thomas Clarkson was the key speaker at the World Anti-Slavery Convention it held in London in 1840.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In the principalities of Wallachia and Moldavia, the government held slavery of the Roma (often referred to as Gypsies) as legal at the beginning of the 19th century.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The progressive pro-European and anti-Ottoman movement, which gradually gained power in the two principalities, also worked to abolish that slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Between 1843 and 1855, the principalities emancipated all of the 250,000 enslaved Roma people.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Bartolomé de las Casas was a 16th-century Spanish Dominican priest, the first resident Bishop of Chiapas (Central America, today Mexico).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] As a settler in the New World he witnessed and opposed the poor treatment and virtual slavery of the Native Americans by the Spanish colonists, under the encomienda system.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] He advocated before King Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor on behalf of rights for the natives.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Las Casas for 20 years worked to get African slaves imported to replace natives; African slavery was everywhere and no one talked of ridding the New World of it, though France had abolished slavery in France itself and there was talk in other countries about doing the same.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] However, Las Casas had a late change of heart, and became an advocate for the Africans in the colonies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] His book, *A Short Account of the Destruction of the Indies*, contributed to Spanish passage of colonial legislation known as the New Laws of 1542, which abolished native slavery for the first time in European colonial history.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] It ultimately led to the Valladolid debate, the first European debate about the rights of colonized people.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] During the early 19th century, slavery expanded rapidly in Brazil, Cuba, and the United States, while at the same time the new republics of mainland Spanish America became committed to the gradual abolition of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] During the Spanish American wars for independence (1810–1826), slavery was abolished in most of Latin America, though it continued until 1873 in Puerto Rico, 1886 in Cuba, and 1888 in Brazil (where it was abolished by the *Lei Áurea*, the "Golden Law").
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Chile declared freedom of wombs in 1811, followed by the United Provinces of the River Plate in 1813, Colombia and Venezuela in 1821, but without abolishing slavery completely.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] While Chile abolished slavery in 1823, Argentina did so with the signing of the Argentine Constitution of 1853.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Slavery was abolished in Uruguay during the *Guerra Grande*, by both the government of Fructuoso Rivera and the government in exile of Manuel Oribe.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Throughout the growth of slavery in the American South, Nova Scotia became a destination for black refugees leaving Southern Colonies and United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] While many blacks who arrived in Nova Scotia during the American Revolution were free, others were not.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Black slaves also arrived in Nova Scotia as the property of White American Loyalists.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1772, prior to the American Revolution, Britain determined that slavery could not exist in the British Isles followed by the *Knight v.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Wedderburn* decision in Scotland in 1778.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] This decision, in turn, influenced the colony of Nova Scotia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1788, abolitionist James Drummond MacGregor from Pictou published the first anti-slavery literature in Canada and began purchasing slaves' freedom and chastising his colleagues in the Presbyterian church who owned slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Led by Richard John Uniacke, in 1787, 1789 and again on 11 January 1808, the Nova Scotian legislature refused to legalize slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Two chief justices, Thomas Andrew Lumisden Strange (1790–1796) and Sampson Salter Blowers (1797–1832) were instrumental in freeing slaves from their owners in Nova Scotia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] They were held in high regard in the colony.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] By the end of the War of 1812 and the arrival of the Black Refugees, there were few slaves left in Nova Scotia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The Slave Trade Act 1807 outlawed the slave trade in the British Empire and the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 outlawed slavery altogether.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] With slaves escaping to New York and New England, legislation for gradual emancipation was passed in Upper Canada (1793) and Lower Canada (1803).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In Upper Canada, the Act Against Slavery of 1793 was passed by the Assembly under the auspices of John Graves Simcoe.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] It was the first legislation against slavery in the British Empire.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Under its provisions no new slaves could be imported, slaves already in the province would remain enslaved until death, and children born to female slaves would be slaves but must be freed at the age of 25.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The last slaves in Canada gained their freedom when slavery was abolished in the entire British Empire by the Slavery Abolition Act 1833.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In his book *The Struggle For Equality*, historian James M.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] McPherson defines an abolitionist "as one who before the Civil War had agitated for the immediate, unconditional, and total abolition of slavery in the United States".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] He does not include antislavery activists such as Abraham Lincoln or the Republican Party, which called for the gradual ending of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Benjamin Franklin, a slaveholder for much of his life, became a leading member of the Pennsylvania Society for the Abolition of Slavery, the first recognized organization for abolitionists in the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Following the American Revolutionary War, Northern states abolished slavery, beginning with the 1777 Constitution of Vermont, followed by Pennsylvania's gradual emancipation act in 1780.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Other states with more of an economic interest in slaves, such as New York and New Jersey, also passed gradual emancipation laws, and by 1804, all the Northern states had abolished it, although this did not mean that already enslaved people were freed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Some had to work without wages as "indentured servants" for two more decades, although they could no longer be sold.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The 1836–1837 campaign to end free speech in Alton, Illinois, culminated in the 7 November 1837 mob murder of abolitionist newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy, which was covered in newspapers nationwide, causing a rise in membership in abolitionist societies.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] By 1840 more than 15,000 people were members of abolitionist societies in the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In the 1850s in the fifteen states constituting the American South, slavery was legally established.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] While it was fading away in the cities as well as in the border states, it remained strong in plantation areas that grew cotton for export, or sugar, tobacco, or hemp.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] According to the 1860 United States census, the slave population in the United States had grown to four million.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] American abolitionism was based in the North, although there were anti-abolitionist riots in several cities.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In the South abolitionism was illegal, and abolitionist publications, like The Liberator, could not be sent to Southern post offices.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Amos Dresser, a white alumnus of Lane Theological Seminary, was publicly whipped in Nashville, Tennessee, for possessing abolitionist publications.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In addition, laws were passed to further repress slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] These laws included anti-literacy laws and anti-gathering laws.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The anti-gathering laws were applied to religious gatherings of free blacks and slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] These laws, passed around the 1820–1850 period, were blamed in the South on Northern abolitionists.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] As one slaveowner wrote, "I can tell you.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Abolitionism in the United States became a popular expression of moralism, operating in tandem with other social reform efforts, such as the temperance movement, and much more problematically, the women's suffrage movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The white abolitionist movement in the North was led by social reformers, especially William Lloyd Garrison (founder of the American Anti-Slavery Society) and writers Wendell Phillips, John Greenleaf Whittier, and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Black activists included former slaves such as Frederick Douglass and free blacks such as the brothers Charles Henry Langston and John Mercer Langston, who helped found the Ohio Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Some abolitionists said that slavery was criminal and a sin; they also criticized slave owners of using black women as concubines and taking sexual advantage of them.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The Republican Party wanted to achieve the gradual extinction of slavery by market forces, because it believed that free labor was superior to slave labor.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] White Southern leaders said that the Republican policy of blocking the expansion of slavery into the territories made them second-class citizens and, as the *Dred Scott* decision held, infringed slaveholders' property rights.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] With the 1860 presidential victory of Abraham Lincoln, seven Deep South states whose economy was based on cotton and the labor of enslaved people decided to secede and form a new nation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The American Civil War broke out in April 1861 with the Confederacy's firing on Fort Sumter, a Union fort in South Carolina.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Meanwhile, four slave states, known as the border states (Maryland, Missouri, Delaware, and Kentucky), chose to remain in the Union.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] On 16 April 1862, Abraham Lincoln signed the District of Columbia Compensated Emancipation Act, abolishing slavery in Washington D.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Meanwhile, the Union suddenly found itself dealing with a steady stream of escaped slaves from the South rushing to Union lines.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In response, Congress passed the Confiscation Acts, which essentially declared escaped slaves from the South to be confiscated war property, called contrabands, so that they would not be returned to their masters in the Confederacy.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] On 1 January 1863, Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which was an executive order of the U.S. government that changed the legal status of 3 million slaves in the Confederacy from "slave" to "henceforward ... free".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Though slaves were legally freed by the Proclamation, they became actually free by escaping to federal lines, or by advances of federal troops.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Even before the Emancipation Proclamation, many former slaves served the federal army as teamsters, cooks, laundresses, and laborers, as well as scouts, spies, and guides.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Plantation owners sometimes moved the Black people they claimed to own as far as possible out of reach of the Union army.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] By "Juneteenth" (19 June 1865, in Texas), the Union Army controlled all of the Confederacy and liberated all its slaves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The owners were never compensated; nor were freed slaves compensated by former owners.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The border states were exempt from the Emancipation Proclamation, but they too (except Delaware) began their own emancipation programs.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] As the war dragged on, both the federal government and Union states continued to take measures against slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In June 1864, the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850, which required free states to aid in returning escaped slaves to slave states, was repealed.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The state of Maryland abolished slavery on 13 October 1864.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Missouri abolished slavery on 11 January 1865.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] West Virginia, which had been admitted to the Union in 1863 as a slave state, but on the condition of gradual emancipation, fully abolished slavery on 3 February 1865.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Constitution took effect in December 1865, seven months after the end of the war, and finally ended slavery for non-criminals throughout the United States.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] It also abolished slavery among the Indian tribes, including the Alaska tribes that became part of the U.S. in 1867.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Brazil and Cuba abolished slavery in the 1880s, with Cuba ending it in 1886 and Brazil in 1888.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] While actors like Gertrudis Gómez de Avellaneda in Cuba and Adelina Charuteira in Brazil worked to end slavery, it was enslaved people themselves who worked daily to chip away at enslavers' local authority.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] These practices are regionally specific based on the legal customs of the region that enslaved people knew well from centuries of interactions with Iberian slave laws.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] A key avenue for these legal arguments was the prominence of "lo extrajudicial", a field of legal interactions adjacent to a lawsuit explained by historian Bianca Premo as consisting of out-of-court settlements, public revelations, and face-to-face encounters.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The suffering of women in slavery was a common trope consistently used in abolitionists' rhetoric on both sides of the Atlantic.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] This was especially true as it relates to the image of suffering mothers and their children.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Towards the end of the nineteenth century as slavery was coming to an end throughout the Atlantic world, images appearing in abolitionist publications routinely included images of families being torn apart and pregnant women being forced to do hard labor.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] As countries imposed "free womb laws" to soften the image of slavery and bring about gradual emancipation, for many it raised the question of the justice of women being used to carry out emancipation without benefiting from it themselves.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Speeches given on the topic at the time focused on mothers and compared them to "all other mothers", using motherhood to level the subjects and objects of their speech.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Women were also often on the forefront of the abolition movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Authors such as Harriet Beecher Stowe (United States) and Gertrudis Gómez de Avellaneda (Brazil) used their novels to call into question the humanity of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Women such as the Grimké Sisters, Abigail Adams, Elizabeth Cady Stanton and others used their connections to political movements to advocate for the abolition of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Enslaved women such as Phillis Wheatley and Harriet Tubman took matters into their own hands by challenging the institution of slavery through their writing and their actions.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Enslaved women like Adelina Charuteira used their mobility as street vendors and as much access as they had to literacy to spread information about abolition between freedom-seeking people and local abolitionist networks.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] White and black opponents of slavery, who played a considerable role in the movement.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] This list includes some escaped slaves, who were traditionally called abolitionists.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The first international attempt to address the abolition of slavery was the World Anti-Slavery Convention, organised by the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society at Exeter Hall in London, on 12–23 June 1840.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] This was however an attempt made by NGOs, not by state and governments.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In the late 19th century, the issue was addressed on an international level by states and governments.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The Brussels Anti-Slavery Conference 1889–90 addressed slavery on a semi-global level via the representatives of the colonial powers.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] It had concluded with the Brussels Conference Act of 1890.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The 1890 Act was revised by the Convention of Saint-Germain-en-Laye 1919.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] During the 20th century the issue of slavery was addressed by the League of Nations, which founded commissions to investigate and eradicate the institution of slavery and slave trade worldwide.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The Temporary Slavery Commission (TSC), which was founded in 1924, conducted a global investigation and filed a report, and a convention was drawn up to hasten the total abolition of slavery and the slave trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The 1926 Slavery Convention, which was founded upon the investigation of the TSC of the League of Nations, was a turning point in banning global slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In 1932, the League formed the Committee of Experts on Slavery (CES) to review the result and enforcement of the 1926 Slavery Convention, which resulted in a new international investigation under the first permanent slavery committee, the Advisory Committee of Experts on Slavery (ACE).
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The ACE conducted a major international investigation on slavery and slave trade, inspecting all the colonial empires and the territories under their control between 1934 and 1939.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Article 4 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted in 1948 by the UN General Assembly, explicitly banned slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] After World War II, chattel slavery was formally abolished by law in almost the entire world, with the exception of the Arabian Peninsula and some parts of Africa.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Chattel slavery was still legal in Saudi Arabia, in Yemen, in the Trucial States and in Oman, and slaves were supplied to the Arabian Peninsula via the Red Sea slave trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The United Nations 1956 Supplementary Convention on the Abolition of Slavery was convened to outlaw and ban slavery worldwide, including child slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In November 1962, Faisal of Saudi Arabia finally prohibited the owning of slaves in Saudi Arabia, followed by the abolition of slavery in Yemen in 1962, slavery in Dubai 1963 and slavery in Oman in 1970.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In December 1966, the UN General Assembly adopted the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, which was developed from the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Article 4 of this international treaty bans slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The treaty came into force in March 1976 after it had been ratified by 35 nations.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] As of November 2003, 104 nations had ratified the treaty.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] However, illegal forced labor involves millions of people in the 21st century, 43% for sexual exploitation and 32% for economic exploitation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Currently, the Anti-trafficking Coordination Team Initiative (ACT Team Initiative), a coordinated effort between the U.S.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Departments of Justice, Homeland Security, and Labor, addresses human trafficking.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] The International Labour Organization estimates that there are 20.9 million victims of human trafficking globally, including 5.5 million children, of which 55% are women and girls.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] In societies with large proportions of the population working in conditions of slavery or serfdom, stroke-of-the-pen laws declaring abolition can have thorough-going social, economic and political consequences.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p01] Issues of compensation/redemption, land-redistribution and citizenship can prove intractable.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] People in modern times have commemorated abolitionist movements and the abolition of slavery in different ways around the world.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] The United Nations General Assembly declared 2004 the International Year to Commemorate the Struggle against Slavery and its Abolition.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] This proclamation marked the bicentenary of the proclamation of the first modern slavery-free state, Haiti.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Numerous exhibitions, events and research programmes became associated with the initiative.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] 2007 witnessed major exhibitions in British museums and galleries to mark the anniversary of the 1807 abolition act – 1807 Commemorated 2008 marked the 201st anniversary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade in the British Empire.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] It also marked the 175th anniversary of the abolition of slavery in the British Empire.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] The Faculty of Law at the University of Ottawa held a major international conference entitled, "Routes to Freedom: Reflections on the Bicentenary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade", from 14 to 16 March 2008.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Abolitionist constitutionalism is a line of thinking which invokes the historical view of the Constitution of the United States as an abolitionist document.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] It calls for an appeal to constitutionalism and progressive constitutionalism.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] This vision is interdisciplinary and finds its roots in the anti-slavery movement in the United States of America and is largely based on the tenet that current state institutions, particularly the carceral system, is rooted in the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Some constitutional abolitionists critique the claim that the Constitution was pro-slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Radical abolitionist constitutionalism calls for the idea of dignity and the use of jurisprudence to address social inequalities.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Constitution was pro-slavery, the Reconstruction Amendments can be seen as a compromise for freedom, without allowing for the full abolition.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Criminal punishment was a major way that Southern states maintained the exploitation of black labor and effectively nullified the Reconstruction Amendments.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] This was done namely through Black Codes, harsh vagrancy laws, apprenticeship laws and extreme punishment for black people.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] The Reconstruction Amendments in their aim to promote citizenship and emancipation are believed by these thinkers to still be guiding principles in the fight for freedom and abolition.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] There are suggestions that a broad reading of the Thirteenth Amendment can convey an abolitionist vision of the freedom advocated for by black people in the public sphere beyond emancipation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Section one of the Fourteenth Amendment was used by many abolitionist lawyers and activists throughout the North to advance the case against slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Proponents of abolitionist constitutionalism believe the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Amendments can be used today to extend the abolitionist logics to the various current barriers to injustices that are faced by marginalized peoples.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Just like abolitionism more generally, abolitionist constitutionalism seeks to provide a vision which will lead to the abolition of many different neoliberal state institutions, such as the prison industrial complex, the wage system, and policing.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] This is tied to a belief that white supremacy is woven into the fabric of legal state institutions.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Radical abolitionists are often marginalized.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] There is a belief that constitutionalism as a main tenet of radical abolitionism can change and appeal to the popular opinion more.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Historically, slavery abolitionists have had to use the public meaning of Constitutional terms in order in their fight against slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Constitutional abolitionists are generally in favour of incremental changes that follow the principles of the Reconstructive Amendments.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Some argue that the narrative and scholarly literature around Reconstruction Amendments is not coherent regarding their original aims.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] On 10 December 1948, the General Assembly of the United Nations adopted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Although outlawed in most countries, slavery is nonetheless practised secretly in many parts of the world.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Enslavement still takes place in the United States, Europe, and Latin America, as well as parts of Africa, the Middle East, and South Asia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Modern slavery keeps around 50 million people from exercising their freedom.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] In Mauritania alone, estimates are that up to 600,000 men, women and children, or 20% of the population, are enslaved.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Modern-day abolitionists have emerged over the last several years, as awareness of slavery around the world has grown, with groups such as Anti-Slavery International, the American Anti-Slavery Group, International Justice Mission, and Free the Slaves working to rid the world of slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] In the United States, The Action Group to End Human Trafficking and Modern-Day Slavery is a coalition of NGOs, foundations and corporations working to develop a policy agenda for abolishing slavery and human trafficking.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Since 1997, the United States Department of Justice has, through work with the Coalition of Immokalee Workers, prosecuted six individuals in Florida on charges of slavery in the agricultural industry.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] These prosecutions have led to freedom for over 1000 enslaved workers in the tomato and orange fields of South Florida.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] This is only one example of the contemporary fight against slavery worldwide.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Slavery exists most widely in agricultural labor, apparel and sex industries, and service jobs in some regions.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] In 2000, the United States passed the Victims of Trafficking and Violence Protection Act (TVPA) "to combat trafficking in persons, especially into the sex trade, slavery, and involuntary servitude".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] The 13th amendment abolished slavery in the United States "except as a punishment for crime whereof the party shall have been duly convicted".
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] In 2018, Colorado became the first state to remove similar language in its state constitution by a legislatively referred ballot referendum.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abolitionism-p02] Other states have followed suit, but implementation has relied on court rulings.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abraham-lincoln-and-slavery-p01] Abraham Lincoln's position on slavery in the United States is one of the most discussed aspects of his life.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abraham-lincoln-and-slavery-p01] Lincoln frequently expressed his moral opposition to slavery.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abraham-lincoln-and-slavery-p01] However, the question of what to do about it and how to end it, given that it was so firmly embedded in the nation's constitutional framework and in the economy of much of the country, even though concentrated in only the Southern United States, was complex and politically challenging.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abraham-lincoln-and-slavery-p01] There was also the question, which Lincoln had to deal with, of what would become of the four million slaves if liberated: how they would earn a living in a society that had almost always rejected them or looked down on their very presence.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abraham-lincoln-and-slavery-p01] In the 1850s, Lincoln was accused of being an abolitionist.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abraham-lincoln-and-slavery-p01] But in 1860, he was attacked as not abolitionist enough: Wendell Phillips charged that, if elected, Lincoln would waste four years trying to decide whether to end slavery in the District of Columbia.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abraham-lincoln-and-slavery-p01] Many abolitionists emphasized the sinfulness of slave owners, but Lincoln did not.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abraham-lincoln-and-slavery-p01] In his 1854 Peoria, Illinois, speech, he said, "I have no prejudice against the Southern people.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abraham-lincoln-and-slavery-p01] They are just what we would be in their situation.
[src:amelioration-act-1798/abraham-lincoln-and-slavery-p01] If slavery did not now exist amongst them, they would not introduce it.
